<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Here are business briefs from Middle
East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The World Gold Council has announced that gold demand
in Saudi Arabia hit a record high of 71.1 tonnes in the first
quarter of this year, up 4.5 percent for the 68 tonnes a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The demand would have been higher had it not been for the Asian
financial crisis, which lowered the number of pilgrims from
Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An exhibition on the latest data technology in the
Middle East and North Africa, the largest of its kind, is to open
Saturday at the Cairo Center of International Conference, Cairo
press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the four-day exhibition, known as
"COMDEX-Egypt," are 125 companies from 11 countries including
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Bahrain, the
United States, France, Britain and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Public Business Sector Atef Mohamed Ebeid
will inaugurate the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Arab-Palestinian Investment Company (APIC) is to
merge with the Al Aqad Company for Palestinian Development, and
the 42 million U.S. dollars of issued capital owned by the latter
will be turned over to the APIC, Al Hayat newspaper reported
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
