<HEADLINE> Mugabe Warns Against Reduction of Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Friday warned that current government efforts to streamline the
Zimbabwe National Army (ZNA) should not result in the reduction of
the 40,000-strong force to levels that could deprive the
country of the means to defence itself.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at a passout parade of 65 ZNA officer cadets at the
Zimbabwe Military Academy in Grewu of central Zimbabwe, Mugabe said
these changes should only be designed to match the organizational
requirements with available financial resources, the zimbabwe news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
''The culmination of this policy should, however, never be the
injudicious reduction of our national army to levels that will
deprive us of an adequate capacity to cope with situations that could
arise in future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe stressed that the maintenance of a well-trained and sufficiently
equipped defence force is a prerequisite for an effective defence
deterrent posture against any would-be external aggressors.
</P>
<P>
He commended the officer cadets course for its nature of being
involving and comprehensive as it aimed at building an officer who
exudes confidence, professionalism and integrity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
