<HEADLINE> IAEA to Monitor Russia's Nuclear Material </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has
promised that the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) could
monitor and control 40 percent of all nuclear material from
scrapped nuclear weapons in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Director-general of the IAEA, Mohamed El Baradei, spoke Friday
during his visit to a nuclear power station.
</P>
<P>
The group will have access to the surveillance and control
system of a joint production base named "beacon," which is located
in Chelyabinsk, where the material will be stored in the year
2000, Baradei said.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA chief said Moscow has committed itself to disarming
nuclear weapons with a set timetable in accordance with
international pacts related to nuclear weapons destruction.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, he tried to discourage the intentions of three
other nations, India, Pakistan and Iran, to develop nuclear weapon.
</P>
<P>
The 127-members IAEA is an inter-governmental body which came
into being in 1957. Its major objectives are to enlarge the
contributions of atomic energy to peace, health and prosperity
worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
