<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar on Capital Market Development in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government and the
Asian Development Bank (ADB) on Friday jointly organized a seminar
here on the development of the capital market in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Findings of a study on the capital market development in Nepal
were presented at the seminar, the ADB said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Participants were told that the development of the capital
market and that of the private sector as a whole are closely
related, and that reforms are needed in five major areas.
</P>
<P>
The five areas are civil service, tax administration, provision
of powers of enforcement for security regulators, modernization of
the system of law and justice, and allowance of foreign banks and
professional advisors such as securities houses, chartered
accountants and auditors to be established here.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Finance Minister Ram Saran Mahat reviewed the impact of
the initial reforms in Nepal some five years back, and emphasized
the need for continuity in the policy and strategies of economic
development and their effective implementation.
</P>
<P>
One of the objectives of privatization underway in Nepal is to
propagate the broader and democratic ownership concept, Mahat
said.
</P>
<P>
Ali Shah, ADB's resident representative in Nepal, stressed the
role the private sector has to play in the development of any
country, and the necessity of having a well-functioning and
transparent capital market where the private sector can turn to
for long-term risk barring capital.
</P>
<P>
A round-table discussion was held before the seminar ended.
Participants discussed the need for greater market transparency,
better auditing standard and better disclosure of information,
better corporate governance, and a wider participation in the
capital market, ADB said.
</P>
<P>
The feedback from the participants will be included in the
final report due to be discussed with the Nepali government in
July, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The participants represented various ministries and agencies,
the private sector, professional associations in Nepal and the
donor community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
