<HEADLINE> Russian Journalists Congress Opens in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The sixth congress of the Union of
Russian Journalists opened here Friday with more than 300
delegates from Russia attending, Itar-Tass news reported.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the meeting, President Boris Yeltsin said, "The
Russian press faces quite a few serious problems today."
</P>
<P>
He said that the law on mass media does not always work, and
different political forces and economic groups continue their
incessant attempts to make the press serve their interests.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, independent newspapers, radio and television
companies are facing financial problems.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin expressed hope that the mass media and the union will
actively defend their rights.
</P>
<P>
Union Chairman Vsevolod Bogdanov said: "We admit that we
represent no power, but we are categorically against being in the
service of authorities, banks and the mafia."
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that his union is taking pains to raise funds
to ease its own financial problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
