<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Countries Urged to Faciliate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Lands and Agriculture
Minister Kumbirai Kangai Friday called on countries in the
southern African region to formulate policies that provide a
conducive enrironment for farmers, traders and processors to do
their business.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a one-day workshop on agricultural industry
stakeholders here, the Zimbabwean minister noted studies that had
been carried out in east Africa and some southern African
countries identified and analysed constraints to formal trade.
</P>
<P>
Informal crossborder trade, Kangai said, was dominated by
agricultural products such as maize, meat, sugar, cooking oil,
investock and other foods.
</P>
<P>
''Differences in formal and informal prices, comparative
advantages that lead to this informal trade and many other trade
related issues have been examined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the common concern in the region was
economic and social development and the immediate focus was the
alleviatiion of poverty which remained widespread in both urban
and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Increased agricultural production and trade in agricultural
products could contribute significantly to not only economic
growth, but to regional food security as well, Kangai said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the issues that came under focus at the workshop
include the development of an agricultural directory which will
assist in easily identifying major stakeholders and what they do.
</P>
<P>
An agricultural comparative advantage report on Zimbabwe which
analyzed the country's competitiveness in the production and
trading of agricultural produce to assist the region to develop
sustainable food security policies was also discussed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
