<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Conservative Party Calls for Tough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Christian Social Union (CSU), the
Bavarian sister party of German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union (CDU), Friday urged tightening up of the
country's asylum rules to stem the inflows of foreign immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"Germany is not an immigration nation," argued the CSU in a
policy paper adopted at a party congress in the southern German
city of Ingolstadt.
</P>
<P>
The Bavaria-based conservative party Friday also reiterated its
rejection to granting dual citizenship to foreigners living in
Germany and called for swift deportation of those foreigners who
have committed serious crimes in Germany.
</P>
<P>
"Bavaria and Germany have reached the limit of ability to take
in foreign immigrants," argued Munich CSU leader, Peter Gauweiler.
"Man cannot embrace the whole world while neglecting its own
people," he added.
</P>
<P>
The hardline demand of the CSU, however, triggered sharp
criticism from opposition parties as well as the Free Democratic
Party (FDP), which is the junior partner in Kohl's center-right
ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
The FDP has been pressing for a more liberal policy to make it
earlier for the nation's 7 million foreigners to integrate into
German society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
