<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Denies Allegation of US Missile Technology Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A veteran Chinese expert on carrier
rocket technology today denied that a US satellite company helped
China to improve its missile guidance and control system during
the investigation of the launching failure of China's Long March
rocket in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Li Jianzhong, president of the
China Academy of Launch Vehicle Technology, accused some people
and media organizations in the United State of spreading
groundless fabrications.
</P>
<P>
As an expert who experienced the whole investigation process of
the launching failure, Li said that China invited six experts from
the United States, Britain and Germany to form an assessment
group in line with the international practice.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the investigation was to obtain reference for
the insurance sector and clients to make decisions, he said,
adding that the action was irreproachable.
</P>
<P>
China has, in the past three decades, developed space technology
by relying entirely on itself, and made remarkable achievements in
this field, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said China has never expected to obtain technology from
other countries by entering the international rocket launching
market.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he stressed, China had found out the cause of the
launch failure and taken proper improvement measures even before
it formed the assessment group.
</P>
<P>
The two cases of successful launching of the Long March 3B last
year were achieved by China itself, without help from the US
satellite company, Li noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
