<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile Great Wall Corp. Refutes Claims of US Role in China Missile Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 22 (Xinhua) -- "Some US citizens and media
purposely fabricated the story about US satellite manufacturers
exposing missile technology to China. There was no such thing,"
said Liu Zhixiong, vice-president of the China Great Wall Industry
Corporation, today.
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remark at a press conference sponsored by the
corporation in response to stories recently disseminated by some
US media and citizens, which claimed that US satellite
manufacturers had helped China to improve its missile guidance and
control systems during the investigation of the Long March launch
vehicle failure which took place February 15, 1996.
</P>
<P>
"It is ridiculous and irresponsible for these stories to be
elaborated one after the other, until there is even talk
of 'endangering national security'," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
A failure analysis panel composed of experts from the Chinese
aerospace industry had already pinpointed the failure before the
participation of the Independent Review Committee (IRC). The
latter was set up at the request of the international insurance
underwriters, who insisted that an analysis team made up of
scientists and engineers from various countries be formed to
review the investigation findings, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The function of the IRC was to review the failure
investigation findings, and had no responsibility to help the
Chinese side to resolve any kind of technical problems. Nor did it
do so. This was a totally normal and commercial practice," he
emphasized, adding that the action taken by the US government to
detain the IRC's report upset the international insurance
community.
</P>
<P>
Liu pointed out that the setting up of the IRC, its composition
and its activities were all completely open. The two US
corporations involved -- Space System/Loral and Hughes Space and
Communications -- were involved because they had direct and purely
commercial business relations.
</P>
<P>
The fact is that the INTELSAT 708 satellite, the contracted
Mabuhay Agila satellite and the contracted APStar 2R satellite
were all manufactured by Space Systems/Loral, while the contracted
APStar 1A and ChinaSat 7 satellites were made by Hughes Space and
Communications, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes U.N. Position on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has said it
was satisfied with the U.N. Security Council's rejection of
Turkish Cypriots' demand to change the bi-communal talks into a
state-to-state negotiation.
</P>
<P>
"The position of the U.N. Security Council, which insists on
relevant U.N. resolutions, strengthens our efforts for a just and
viable solution to the Cyprus problem," government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said Friday at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Thursday stressed that efforts for a
Cyprus settlement should continue through bi-communal talks.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said that the Council's position constituted "a
reply to (Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf) Denktash's unacceptable
demand, as well as to the substance of a solution to the Cyprus
problem."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 the "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify the island
under a bi-zonal and bi-communal formula.
</P>
<P>
Last summer, the Turkish Cypriots walked out of the
U.N.-sponsored peace talks to protest the European Union's (EU's)
decision to start accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has since insisted on recognition of his breakaway
state before negotiations can be resumed, and on the withdrawal of
Cyprus' application for the EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
