<HEADLINE> Nepali King Meets With Former Gurkha Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Nepali King Birendra granted an
audience on Friday evening to four former Gurkha soldiers who were
honored with the Victoria Cross, the highest honor medal of the
British army.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the king to grant an audience to
former Gurkha soldiers who were honored with the Victoria Cross.
</P>
<P>
A total of 13 Nepalese who served in the British army had
received the Victoria Cross for acts of bravery during the First
and Second World Wars. Six of them have died.
</P>
<P>
The four who had an audience with the king were Captain Ganju
Lama, Captain Agam Singh Rai, rifleman Laxman Gurung and Captain
Ram Bahadur Limbu, said Kul Raj Limbu, general secretary of the
Gurkha Memorial Trust, an organization of the ex-Gurkha soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 3,000 Nepalese are still serving in the
British army.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in 1947 between Nepal, Britain and
India, the British and Indian armies can recruit Nepalese, who
have been popularly known as the Gurkha soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
