<HEADLINE> UNICEF Protests Latest Sierra Leone Outrages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) Friday called for concerted international
action to ensure child protection in Sierra Leone where atrocity
has been escalating.
</P>
<P>
Over 300 Sierra Leone civilians, including women and children,
have been tortured by remnants of the ousted Armed Forces
Revolutionary Council and the rebels of the Revolutionary United
Front in the past two weeks, UNICEF said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency quoted latest news reports as saying that
civilians have been tortured and mutilated, some suffering from
amputations of their hands, ears, breasts and genitals.
</P>
<P>
The democratically-elected government in the 4.5 million
population the West African country returned to power in March
after six months in exile, but the rebels are still operating in
some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
"In almost all conflict zones, the world is daily confronted
with unspeakable violations of the rights of children," UNICEF
Director-General Carol Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
In Sierra Leone, over 55 percent of children aged 6-14 are out
of school, according to UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy called on donors to respond generously to flash U.N.
aid appeal totaling 4 million U.S. dollars for Sierra Leone for
the period March-May 1998. So far only one fifth of the request
has been fulfilled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
