<HEADLINE> Rafsanjani on U.S. Failure to Isolate Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran's former President Hashemi
Rafsanjani said Friday that the U.S. retreat from sanctions on
Iran was a major victory for the Iranian nation.
</P>
<P>
"The recent U.S. measures for partial abrogation of sanctions
on Iran is not only a clear retraction of illogical
extra-territorial laws, but also a major victory for the Iranian
nation," Rafsanjani said at a Friday prayer congregation.
</P>
<P>
Calling the D'Amato and Helmz-Burton laws as an indication of
the U.S. domineering policy, Rafsanjani said that, by taking such
measures unilaterally, U.S. was like taking a big bite that it was
incapable of swallowing, the Iranian official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton announced Tuesday that Washington
decided not to impose sanctions on the French, Russian and
Malaysian companies which have had a contract totaling 2 billion
U.S. dollars with Iran to tap an Iranian offshore gas field in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
According to the D'Amato law signed by Clinton in 1996,
Washington would punish any company which has more than 40 million
U.S. dollars in investments in the energy sector of Iran and
Libya. The ceiling was reduced to 20 million dollars last August.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. retreat was also believed by Tehran as a failure of
Washington's efforts to isolate Tehran through accusations that
Iran was undermining the Middle East peace process, seeking
nuclear weapons and supporting terrorism. 
</P>
