<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radiation Leaks Trigger Outcries in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The recent revelations of radioactive
contaminations of German nuclear waste convoys have triggered a
wave of outcries in Germany with the parliament planning to hold a
special session next week to clarify the government's role in the
incidents.
</P>
<P>
At issue is a recent finding that many nuclear waste containers
shipped from Germany to French reprocessing plants had excess
outside radioactivity.
</P>
<P>
The German authorities also revealed earlier this month that
there had been 11 cases of excess radioactivity on German waste
convoys in 1997 out of a total of 55 convoys.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Bonn has ordered the suspension of all nuclear
waste shipments both within the country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Greenpeace and German opposition parties however accused
the government of having been informed of the contaminations
several years ago but having failed to stop the shipments earlier.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the charge, the Environment Ministry said that it was
informed of the problem by the French side for the first time at
the end of April. Moreover, no contaminations had been reported in
Germany so far.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also sharply criticized the atomic industry after
the latter admitted that they had been informed of the excess
radioactivity as early as the mid-1980s but had not asked the
government for help.
</P>
<P>
The latest revelations also provoked strong protests from the
German police which have to deploy large troops every year to
protect inland transport of nuclear wastes amid widespread
anti-nuclear protests.
</P>
<P>
German Environment Minister Angela Merkel insisted Friday that
the government had not done anything wrong. She also welcomed the
parliament debate scheduled for next week, saying that it would
help to clarify the whole issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chadian Southern Rebels Surrender to Gov't Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Chadian rebels fighting for a federal
state in the southern part of the country have surrendered to
government forces after six months of fighting, according to
reports from Chad.
</P>
<P>
The Forces Armees pour la Republic Federale (FARF), a
political-military group which has hundreds of desert fighters,
signed on May 8 with President Idris Deby a truce in exchange for
an amnesty.
</P>
<P>
FARF leader Laokein Barde has reportedly fled the country.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people, mostly civilians, have been killed during
the fighting between the FARF and government forces, which were
reportedly supported by France.
</P>
<P>
Fighting began on October 30, 1997, when the government forces
tried to dispel the FARF from the southern city of Moundou.
</P>
<P>
The special force "nomad guards," trained by French troops from
1994 to 1996, brutally suppressed the villagers in the war zone
and mainly targeted civilians for extortions, said reports.
</P>
<P>
The conflict was the last episode of the north-south fighting
in Chad which has marked the history of the Sahel nation ever
since its independence from France in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The southerners called for the establishment of a federal
state, which would allow them, mostly Christians and animists, to
escape the hegemony of northerners, mostly Muslims, who have
dominated the country since the victory of President Hissene Habre
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The end of the conflict in the southern part of Chad will allow
the government to start oil explorations in the region, reportedly
rich in petroleum deposits, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
France has been maintaining about 1,000 soldiers in Chad under
a military agreement as well as an air force squadron deployed in
the 1980s under the Epervier operation aimed at fending off Libyan
invasion.
</P>
<P>
A small number of French troops stayed in the southern part of
Chad throughout the six-month conflict to train government
soldiers engaging the FARF fighters.
</P>
<P>
Paris is blamed by local villagers for ignoring open violence
inflicted upon civilians by government forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Referendum Turnout for Northern Irish Peace High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Chief Electoral Officer in Northern
Ireland Pat Bradley said Friday that turnout in the referendum on
the peace agreement was a record high.
</P>
<P>
"It's been very consistent and persistent, and that would seem
to indicate a high turnout if it continues at this level," Bradley
said in an interview on BBC Ulster.
</P>
<P>
"If it's a high poll, clearly there are more ballot papers to
be counted. But I am hopeful that we could have a result early to
mid-afternoon," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bradley said voters had cast ballots steadily throughout the
day, which was unusual.
</P>
<P>
In some areas of the province, including Belfast and Lurgan,
queues formed outside polling stations before they open at 7:00 in
the morning. Voting has also been brisk in the Irish Republic,
according to a BBC report from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, leader of the biggest Protestant party in
Northern Ireland, the Ulster Unionists, said voting was running at
a higher level than usual. "That confirms a general expectation
that there will be a high turnout," he said.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal sets out new arrangements for the internal
administration of Northern Ireland and for new cross-border bodies
designed to improve cooperation between the north and south of
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for changes to the Irish constitution which
alters the republic's claim to Northern Ireland so that it talks
of uniting people rather than territory.
</P>
<P>
Security forces have been on alert throughout the day to guard
against possible attacks by militants on both sides, but so far
there have been no reported incidents or injuries in the voting.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations will be closed at 10:00 pm. Counting begins at
9:00 am Saturday and final results are expected to come out in the
afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
