<HEADLINE> Russian Foreign Ministry: Russia Needs START-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry Friday
said that Russia needs ratification of the START-2 (strategic
arms reduction treaty) more than the United States does.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency quoted Vladimir Rahmanin, the Foreign
Ministry's spokesman, as saying that ratification of START-2 is "a
crucial issue from the point of view of Russia's security."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a roundtable meeting on the country's geopolitical
priorities at the end of the century, Rahmanin said Russia cannot
afford to maintain a large quantity of missiles and their number
needs to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
A START-3 is necessary for this purpose, which is impossible
without START-2, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The START-2 treaty signed by the United States and Russia in
Moscow in January 1993 was ratified by the U.S. congress in
January 1996. The ratification of the START-2 treaty has been
obstructed by the State Duma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
