<HEADLINE> Security Council Condemns Armed Attack in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations Friday strongly condemned the recent armed attack
in Angola against personnel from the United Nations and the
Angolan National Police.
</P>
<P>
On May 19, a patrol of U.N. personnel and the Angolan National
Police was attacked by armed elements, in which one person was
killed and three people were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
In a presidential statement, the Security Council demanded that
the Government of Unity and National Reconciliation of Angola
(GURN) and in particular the Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) guarantee unconditionally the safety and freedom of
movement of all United Nations and other international personnel.
</P>
<P>
The council strongly deplored the failure by the UNITA to
complete the implementation of its remaining obligations under the
Lusaka Protocol and relevant Security Council resolutions,
especially its failure to cooperate in completing the
normalization of state administration throughout the national
territory.
</P>
<P>
The council called on the GURN and UNITA in the strongest terms
to refrain from any action which may lead to renewed hostilities
or derail the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The council warned that if the UNITA fails to fulfill its
obligations in accordance with the Lusaka Protocol, it will
consider the imposition of additional measures on the UNITA.
</P>
</TEXT>
