<HEADLINE> Greece Urges EU Members Not to Send Wrong Messages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Greece urged Friday the European
Union (EU) members not to send wrong messages to Turkey to hurt
Greece's interests.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his talks with Britain's special envoy for the
Cyprus problem, Sir David Hannay, Greek Foreign Undersecretary
Yiannos Kranidiotis said that EU members should in future refrain
from sending out wrong messages to Turkey by isolating Greece,
such as in their recent decision to convene the union's
association council with Turkey, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He added that the strengthening of Turkey's European
orientation was its own responsibility which that country was
being called upon to assume itself.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated that the EU must defend the decisions
adopted at December's Luxembourg summit concerning the principles
and criteria for an improvement in the relations between Greece
and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
While describing his visit to Greece as "extremely important,"
Hannay, who arrived here Friday for talks with Greek officials,
reportedly told the Greek side that although the British
government was not prepared to endorse a revision of Luxembourg
summit decisions, it considered that there was perhaps need to
discuss certain "clarifications" in Cardiff, Britain, but without
changing the substance of issues.
</P>
<P>
Hannay said that he would visit a number of European countries
to discuss the issues regarding the Euro-Turkish relations, and
then report British Prime Minister Tony Blair ahead of the Cardiff
summit on June 15.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Kranidiotis and Hannay discussed Cyprus'
accession to the EU, the visit by British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook to Turkey, Turkey's decision not to attend the association
council and London's positions in view of the Cardiff summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
