<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Updated) U.S. Senate Votes Sanctions on Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate voted 90 to 4
Friday to impose sanctions on Russia for exporting missile
technology to Iran, but it was expected to be vetoed by President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The measure was passed by the House of Representatives last
November, but with slight differences. The two chambers will
resolve the differences of the versions of the measure before
sending it to the president.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, sanctions include denying arms export licenses
and eliminating all U.S. assistance for two years. The bill allows
the president to waive sanctions for reasons of national security.
</P>
<P>
The administration would be required to report to Congress the
companies or research institutes that have transferred or sought
to transfer missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Sponsors of the legislation accused that Russia had been
helping Iran refine the delivery system of its missiles and that
"numerous Russian entities" had provided other assistance,
including wind tunnels for missile development.
</P>
<P>
The Senate agreed that the sanctions would be applied only on
cases of aid to Iran's missile program after January 1998 when
Russia took steps to control its exports of dual-use technology.
</P>
<P>
"Iran's missile program has been advanced tremendously by
assistance from a wide range of Russian entities," Senate
Republican Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said in explaining his
vote.
</P>
<P>
However, the Clinton administration told Congress this week
that Russia had made progress in controlling exports of missile
technology and needed more time to put a tough nuclear
non-proliferation policy in place.
</P>
<P>
The White House renewed a veto threat. Enactment of the bill
"would weaken the United States' ability to persuade the
international community to halt such transfers to Iran," said a
White House statement released Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
