<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-22 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Cause Floods in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Floods caused by continual heavy
rains in Turkey's western Black Sea region have cut off power and
telephone lines, swept away roads and damaged buildings, virtually
paralyzing these areas.
</P>
<P>
There is so far no report of casualties, mainly because of the
disruption of communications with the area. The main road to
Zonguldak province from the capital Ankara, some 300 kilometers in
length, was ruined by fast-running river water that overflowed.
</P>
<P>
Turkish government, non-governmental organizations and the
armed forces have been mobilized to provide urgent aids to the
flood-stricken people.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said the state would mobilize all
its resources to help the victims, adding that a "crisis center"
had been set up in Ankara in order to track the disaster more
closely and to provide solutions.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 100 people in Karabuk, a city some 200
kilometers northwest of Ankara, were still under siege.
</P>
<P>
Zonguldak Deputy Governor Ahmet Set said that some 100 people
stranded in Zonguldak and its surroundings have been rescued by
helicopters and boats.
</P>
<P>
He said the floods in the districts of Eregli, Alapli, Caycuma,
Gokcebey and Devrek had inflicted heavy damages to local residents.
</P>
<P>
The amount of rainfall in Turkey in last 20 days has already
tripled the average in many previous springs, the country's
Meteorology Directorate said, adding the rain in the Black Sea
region will continue until Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
