<HEADLINE> Iran, Pakistan Discuss Indian Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Friday expressed concern about India's nuclear tests and urged
Pakistan to exercise patience and self-restraint over the issue.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in a telephone conversation with Pakistani
Prime Minister Mohammad Nawaz Sharif, the Iranian official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
"We have always condemned any nuclear test and we are against
proliferation of the nuclear weapons," Khatami was quoted as
saying, "we regard your security as a serious issue, and we fully
understand the circumstances that Pakistani government and people
are undergoing."
</P>
<P>
He said continued nuclear arms race would further deepen
regional crisis and cause environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Sharif accused India of threatening regional peace and security
by detonating nuclear tests, and said Pakistan had refrained from
doing so though it had had the capability, for fear of triggering
regional crisis and an arms race.
</P>
<P>
He said "we are still reviewing the consequences of the nuclear
tests and we have always believed in making wise decisions and
being prudent at such sensitive circumstances."
</P>
<P>
India conducted five underground nuclear tests last week,
triggering off a storm of worldwide condemnations.
</P>
<P>
Some Pakistani officials have warned that Islamabad is under
great pressure from within the country and would explode its own
nuclear devices in the near future in response. 
</P>
</TEXT>
