<HEADLINE> S. Leone Parliament Reopens on Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Nearly three months after the
military junta was driven out of the capital Freetown, the
restored President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah reopened the parliament
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In his address in the chamber of the parliament, he focused in
particular on the security situation, according to a British
Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
Brig.-Gen. Maxwell Kobe, the task force commander of the west
African peacekeeping force ECOMOG in Sierra Leone, is to develop
guidelines for putting together a new national army for the
country, the president told the parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to Kabbah, Nigeria's head of state General Sani
Abacha has agreed to make Kobe, a Nigerian general who led the
battle to chase the junta out of Freetown, available to Sierra
Leone for the reestablishment of the national army.
</P>
<P>
It will be ensured that the Sierra Leonean defense system will
be manned by competent and disciplinary people who see the
military as a noble profession and not a means to achieve their
selfish objectives, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Some junior officers, reportedly disgruntled with their poor
treatment, launched a coup last May that overthrew the legitimate
government of Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, aided by the international community ousted the junta
in mid-February this year and paved the way for the reinstatement
of Kabbah a month later.
</P>
<P>
Not long after his restoration, the president mandated the
ECOMOG commander to take charge of the security all over Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, the president told the parliament that the
past thing in the national security could never happen again.
</P>
<P>
That is "because the government is to create a superior
nationwide intelligence system that will provide full and
accurate information on the security situation in the country,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also reminded Sierra Leoneans that the national
economy is so far on an unprecedented downturn in performance
because of the destruction in production and basic
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
While the government is expecting some progress in some areas
with international support, the president pointed out that Sierra
Leone can go ahead economically and socially only by the efforts
of Sierra Leoneans.
</P>
<P>
He also told the parliament that the government will be
introducing a new law for the establishment of an independent
income tax authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
