<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Protection Against Bio Weapons, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday announced plans to stockpile vaccines and antibiotics for
treatment of Americans in a biological weapons attack and to
protect against cyberspace attack.
</P>
<P>
"If our children are to grow up safe and free, we must approach
these new 21st century threats with the same rigor and
determination we applied to the toughest security challenges of
this century," the president said in a commencement speech at the
U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Mariland.
</P>
<P>
"As we approach the 21st century, our foes have extended the
fields of battle from physical space to cyberspace, from the
world's vast bodies of water to the complex workings of our own
human body. Rather than invading our beaches or launching bombers,
these adversaries may attempt cyber attacks against our critical
military systems and our economic base," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He ordered the development and stockpiling of vaccines and
antibiotics for civilians, and directed that public health and
medical surveillance systems be upgraded to detect and sound the
alarm on any release of bacteria or viruses.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said the United State will launch a comprehensive
plan to detect, deter, and defend against attacks on the nation's
critical infrastructures such as computers that control the stock
market, banking, utilities, and air traffic.
</P>
<P>
"If we fail to take strong action, then terrorists, criminals
and hostile regimes could invade and paralyze these vital systems,
disrupting commerce, threatening health, weakening our capacity to
function in a crisis," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He appointed National Security Council adviser Richard Clarke,
who specializes in such issues as drug trafficking and terrorism,
to head a new commission on infrastructure protection and
counter-terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On the same day the Defense Department expanded its vaccination
program against the lethal anthrax bacteria to include not just
troops in the Gulf region, but all active and reserve personnel.
</P>
<P>
Also, the Pentagon designated 10 states -- Massachusetts, New
York, Pennsylvania, Georgia, Illinois, Texas, Missouri, Colorado,
California and Washington -- where National Guard units will be
specially trained for responding to weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
