<HEADLINE> Syrian Foreign Minister Holds Talks With Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright held talks with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara
at the State Department Friday on the deadlocked Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Their talks were expected to cover both Israel's withdrawal
from the Golan Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
war, and Israel's proposal for conditional withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria has held sporadic peace talks with Israel since 1991 but
the negotiations broke off in early 1996 without making tangible
progress on two major issues -- the fate of the Golan Heights and
future ties between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
No talks have been held since right-wing Likud leader Benjamin
Netanyahu won an election in May 1996 and took office as the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants the talks to resume from the point where they left
off, but Netanyahu, who opposes returning the Golan Heights to
Syria, wants to start talks anew.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Lebanon, both Damascus and Beirut rejected
Israel's proposal for conditional withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria ad Lebanon say Israel should implement U.N. Resolution
425, passed in 1978, which calls for an unconditional pullback of
Israel's 35,000 troops. 
</P>
