<HEADLINE> Commitment Not Enough for Human Rights: Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi said Friday that the existence of the necessary resolve,
determination and commitment and availability of constitutional
provision alone would not be sufficient to ensure the promotion
and protection of citizens' human rights.
</P>
<P>
Closing the five-day international conference on the
establishment of the human rights commission and the office of
the ombudsman, Meles said the availability of the appropriate
institutional framework for effective implementation of
constitutional provisions guaranteeing political and civil rights
is the key for progress.
</P>
<P>
"There is today a growing realization internationally, and a
consensus within the international community, that the effective
promotion and protection of human rights demands that all aspects
of human life and human needs be taken into account in our effort
to promote the rights of the human person," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no better substitute for protecting the human
rights of citizens than their own active, popular and grassroots
participation in politics and their preparedness to expose and
challenge violations and constitutional transgressions.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed his confidence that the
conference has afforded the opportunity to draw lessons on the
approach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
