<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Alternatives Bring Pagers Back to Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 22 (Xinhua) -- PanAmSat, the U.S. company whose
major satellite shifted out of position Tuesday, said today that
satellite service has been restored its paging and other
telecommunications customers.
</P>
<P>
But it added that it may be a few days before all beepers and
other communication devices are working again.
</P>
<P>
The company shifted service to other satellites after
concluding that it would not try to fix its crippled Galaxy IV
satellite, which malfunctioned Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Paging companies, business networks and radio and TV stations
dependent on the old satellite must adjust their antennas toward
the substitute satellite, Galaxy 3R.
</P>
<P>
The 250-million-dollar Galaxy IV rotated out of its proper
position Tuesday when an onboard computer control system failed,
knocking out service to about 45 million pagers across the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The company moved Galaxy IV into a higher orbit Thursday night
and does not plan to restore its communication services, Marcus
said this morning. A replacement satellite will be launched at the
end of next year.
</P>
<P>
By Thursday afternoon, almost 90 percent of the affected
pagers were back in operation, according to a paging industry
trade group.
</P>
<P>
PanAmSat has not determined what caused the computer system to
fail. Officials said there was no evidence that sabotage was
involved or that the satellite was hit by something in space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
