<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals Court Dismisses Lawsuit over 1992 Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals on Friday dismissed a lawsuit that claimed President Bill
Clinton's 1992 election campaign illegally received 1.4 million
dollars in federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
In a 3-0 decision, the court upheld a lower court's dismissal
of the case on grounds that those who brought it did not have
standing, saying they failed to show that they "suffered a
concrete and personalized injury."
</P>
<P>
Nor did they establish a claim that their support for Clinton's
rivals was made less effective because Clinton's campaign received
greater funds with which to sway voters.
</P>
<P>
Judge A. Raymond Randolph described that argument as
"hypothetical." Even if the Clinton campaign received money to
which it was not entitled, it might have spent that money on
brightening its offices or better hotel accommodations, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
In any case, the panel ruled, extra money did not undercut the
ability of those who brought the suit to support Clinton rivals.
</P>
<P>
The three organizations that sued could not claim to have been
disadvantaged as a competitor to Clinton, the court said. Only a
rival candidate could make that claim. And the four voters' claim
that their ability to influence the election's outcome was
undercut was "far too fanciful," the judges ruled.
</P>
<P>
Since it ruled that those who brought the suit lacked legal
status to bring the case, the court did not address the suit's
claim that the Clinton campaign improperly diverted to the general
election certain funds that, by law, could be used only for a
primary campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Calls for Unity, Peace of All African Peoples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Salim Ahmed Salim,
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
Friday called on African peoples to rededicate themselves to
unity, solidarity, peace, harmony and the integrity of all
peoples.
</P>
<P>
The call came from a message by the OAU Secretary-General on
the occasion of the 35th anniversary of the OAU which falls on
May 25.
</P>
<P>
Salim described the 35th anniversary of OAU as "an important
milestone" and noted that "this is a particular stage in its
history that underlines the strong will of its member states to
continue forging a common destiny through their organization."
</P>
<P>
Salim said that "among the major preoccupations within our
collective agenda in the past year has been the pursuit of peace,
security and stability in the region," stressing that "no serious
socio-economic development can be achieved in our countries in
the absence of peace."
</P>
<P>
Summing up the past year's experience, Salim said Africans
"have achieved remarkable success in reducing the areas that are
afflicted by the scourge of conflict".
</P>
<P>
According to Salim, "peace has come to Liberia, the end of
conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo, the Republic of
Congo and also in the Central African Republic gives cause for
hope and optimism:, Rwanda is forging ahead "in the process of
rebuilding the structures and institutions for national
development," and Sierra Leone "has achieved significant and
historic achievement of the restoration of constitutional order."
</P>
<P>
Salim stressed that Africans have also made "remarkable
strides" in economic integration, saying that the first assembly
of heads of state and government of African Economic Community
(AEC) held last year during the 33rd OAU summit in Harare,
Zimbabwe "marked a concrete realization of the 1991 Abuja treaty
that laid out a blue-print for the establishment of the African
Economic Community."
</P>
<P>
With the protocol between the AEC and the regional economic
communities signed in February, this year "opened the way for
enhanced cooperation between the community and the regional
groupings of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), the Southern African Development Community (SADC), the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) and the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD), in a dynamic
partnership," he adds.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that the situation we face today is very
challenging," Salim pointed out, and he noted that "we are also
confident that if we apply ourselves seriously and raise our
determination, we will be able to transform the continent and
overcome the difficulties that we encounter in improving the
conditions of our people."
</P>
<P>
"The accelerated development of the continent as well as its
peace and security depends on collaborative effort between our
governments and peoples in a partnership that is solid and
durable," Salim said, adding that "Africa will certainly have
more chance in addressing its problems when our people work
together in unity, in strength, and in solidarity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
