<HEADLINE> Prices Firm As Tobacco Sales Resume in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tobacco prices surged on
the main tobacco sales floor auction when farmers started selling
Friday reaching a high of 1.64 U.S. Dollars per kg, an
appreciable increase from the 1.25 U.S. Dollars per kg average
price when farmers suspended deliveries last week.
</P>
<P>
President of the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association Robert Webb said
Friday that "We expect the floors to be much more busy after the
weekend holiday, and we hope prices will continue firming."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday the association called on all tobacco growers to
immediately resume full scale deliveries as prices were expected
to firm, after wide and full range discussions with international
merchants and manufacturers over the past week.
</P>
<P>
Last week farmers suspended the sale of tobacco to the auction
floors, protesting against depressed prices, averaging around one
U.S. Dollar per kg, thereby threatening the viability of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco, the country's biggest foreign currency earner,
clinched exports estimated at over 400 million U.S. Dollars this
year. 
</P>
