<HEADLINE> More Southern Sudanese Need Food Aid: WFP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) said
Friday that the number of southern Sudanese facing famine has
risen to 930,000 from originally targeted 700,000.
</P>
<P>
In Bahr El Ghazal Province alone, some 595,000 people need
international food aid, of whom 380,000 are in critical need for
survival, said the WFP Nairobi office. The total figure
represented a 40-percent increase.
</P>
<P>
On March 31, the Khartoum government has granted the U.N. aid
access to Bahr El Ghazal which had been off-limits for nearly two
months. The worsening condition of the people there has prompted
a major emergency intervention.
</P>
<P>
Although the WFP raised its monthly deliveries of food from
2,267 tons in April to an expected 4,000 tons in May, it is still
not enough to meet the emergency food needs of the southern
Sudanese, the U.N. food agency said.
</P>
<P>
WFP said that it is expecting to match the monthly requirement
of 6,500 tons per month for Bahr El Ghazal and other areas of
southern Sudan from the beginning of next month with the arrival
of the fifth Hercules plane.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the agency appealed for a total of 65.8 million
U.S. Dollars to fund aircraft and food supplies over the next 12
months to keep emergency operations in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
So far, it has received 15.4 million U.S. Dollars in confirmed
contributions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
