<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Irish Voters Endorse Peace Deal with Resounding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Voters in Northern Ireland endorsed
the historic peace agreement with a resounding majority of 71
percent, official results showed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chief electoral officer Pat Bradley, who was running the voting
on Friday, announced the final result in Belfast with cheers and
chanting from the supporters of the deal.
</P>
<P>
According to Bradley, turnout in Northern Ireland was also a
record high, with 81.1 percent of eligible voters casting their
ballots.
</P>
<P>
Final results from the Irish Republic were yet to be announced
but partial official returns suggested a massive 95 percent
majority in the republic voted in favor of the agreement that was
thrashed out last month after 22-month hard negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Nearly four million people -- some 1.2 million in Northern
Ireland and about 2.8 million in the Irish Republic -- were
eligible to cast a ballot.
</P>
<P>
Observers had said a 70 percent "Yes" vote in Northern Ireland
would indicate that most Protestants, who were split over the
agreement, had voted in favor.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement proposes maintaining Northern Ireland's
links with Britain while building closer ties with Ireland in a
bid to end a catalogue of bombs, bullets and beatings.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Secretary of State for Northern Ireland Mo Mowlam
told reporters at a news conference in Belfast that the province
had "voted to take the gun out of politics, north and south of the
border."
</P>
<P>
"This agreement is supported across the whole community and in
a majority of both (Protestant and Catholic) communities," she
said.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, leader of the biggest Protestant party, also
hailed the endorsement of the deal, saying: "It is an endorsement
of what we did on the negotiations and it is a very welcome
acceptance by people."
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, leader of Irish Republic Army's political wing
Sinn Fein which wants a united Ireland, said people had taken a
great leap of faith.
</P>
<P>
"What the electorate did was to sign up for a future, not a
past", he told BBC television.
</P>
<P>
After the agreement was approved in the referendum, Northern
Ireland will quickly move to elections in June for the 108-strong
assembly to govern local affairs.
</P>
<P>
It will not have any powers until next year but will press
ahead with arrangements for the cross-border bodies with the south
of the island.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
