<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women in Nepali Village Prefer More Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 23 (Xinhua) -- In the present age of family
planning, women in the village of Bharatipur in Nawalparasi
district of western Nepal still prefer to give birth to more than
10 children, the government-owned Gorkhapatra daily reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Those who fail to bear more than 10 children are subject to
being boycotted from the society, the Nepali-language newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The village, inhabited mainly by the ethnic communities, has
followed the tradition for a long time, villagers said.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 2,500, the village has difficult access to
the outside world due to lack of transportation means. It takes
the villagers three days to reach the nearby highway on foot.
</P>
<P>
Usually, women there get married at an early age, and by the
time they reach 32, they have borne 10 children, which they think
is the gift of God.
</P>
<P>
"We should accept the gift of God, (no matter) how many
children God gives us, we should accept," said 39-year-old Maya
Chhetri. She has 12 children now, but is willing to have more.
</P>
<P>
Most of the villagers are illiterate and very poor. Yet the
educated just have as many children.
</P>
<P>
They know about the family planning but dislike it.
</P>
<P>
Neighbors of Gam Bahadur Thapa, for instance, became
uncooperative with him after he got himself sterilized following
the birth of two children, forcing him and his family to leave the
village.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to generate awareness about the family
planning by the government in this village because people are
doing competition in giving birth to more and more children,"
Chairman of the village development committee Bhupal Rawa was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has a population of 21.6 million and it is growing at a
rate of 2.6 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
The growth of agricultural production has failed to match that
of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin to Invest Heavily in Urban Construction, Pillar Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 23 (Xinhua) -- This north China port city plans to
invest a total of 42.7 billion yuan in urban construction and
pillar industries this year.
</P>
<P>
This was learned at the first session of the 13th Tianjin
Municipal People's Congress, held here today.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be allocated to 48 key projects. The industrial
projects will be mainly in the sectors of electronic information,
biotechnology, advanced manufacturing, new materials, new energy
and environmental protection, which will be built into the city's
new pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some traditional industries, including cement,
polyester, and vehicle engine production, will also be financed.
</P>
<P>
Major urban construction schemes will include the harnessing of
the mainstream of the Haihe River, the building of a coal dock at
Tianjin Port, bringing natural gas from northern Shaanxi to
Tianjin, and the improvement of power, heat and gas supply
networks and sewage systems, and the building of inter-city
highways and city streets.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has invested a total of 38.8 billion yuan in
infrastructure over the past five years, including construction of
expressways, bridges and major streets, expansion of power
supply and housing construction to accommodate 150,000 families.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Zhang Lichang said that he expects that this year's
investment plan will help Tianjin keep its annual GDP growth at 10
percent and retain its status as the economic center for the Bohai
Rim area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
