<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Says "Yes" to Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- People on both sides of the Irish
border voted "yes" to the peace agreement to end 30 years of
Protestant-Catholic bloodshed, official results said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Voters voted for the Northern Ireland peace accord by 71.12
percent to 28.88 percent, Chief Electoral Officer Pat Bradley
announced in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement, which came into being on April 10,
proposes maintaining Northern Ireland's links with Britain, while
building closer ties with Ireland in a bid to end the conflict
between Protestants and Catholics.
</P>
<P>
Chanting "Here we go, here we go," the officer announced
figures showing a turnout of 81.1 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
Observers said a 70 percent majority was needed for "yes"
campaigners to claim the support of a majority from the unionist
community.
</P>
<P>
Early results in the Republic of Ireland suggest a majority of
almost 95 percent had voted for the agreement, with a turnout of
around 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts in Northern Ireland have claimed more than 3,000
lives and injured over thirty thousand. 
