<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Documents Released on Satellite Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The White House released a trove
of documents Friday showing that U.S. President Bill Clinton
permitted satellite launch with China to the American national
interest.
</P>
<P>
The documents, demanded by Congress and made available to the
news media, indicated that the president approved the Chinese
launching of an American satellite last February after his top
staff advised him that the economic and diplomatic advantages
outweighed the opposition of Federal Prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors had warned that the approval would jeopardize
their investigation into the satellite maker's earlier,
unauthorized help to China's rocket program.
</P>
<P>
The documents argued that they showed that the president, while
aware of the risks, approved the launching on the basis of policy
debate and not because the chairman of the satellite company, the
Democratic Party's largest personal contributor, was pressing hard
for a decision.
</P>
<P>
The White House and State Department both denied that there was
a linkage between the decision making and Democratic Party's
fund-raising efforts in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The documents also showed that the State Department and other
agencies had determined that the launch by Loral Space and
Communications Ltd. was in "the national interest" and recommended
approval.
</P>
<P>
The documents were released at a time when congressional
Republicans accused the president of jeopardizing the nation's
security in granting a waiver to the American company. They
suggested that the decision to do so was influenced by campaign
contributions from Loral Chairman Bernard L. Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
The documents were handed over to Congress as the
administration sought to buttress its contention that the
decision to grant the waiver was made on its merits.
</P>
<P>
"These documents reflect the serious policymaking on national
interests grounds that goes into satellite waivers," said White
House spokesman Michael McCurry. "They also make clear that those
who are taking political cheap shots should butt out."
</P>
<P>
President Clinton said in the White House Rose Garden
that his decision was the correct one and "was based on what I
thought was in the national interest and supportive of our
national security."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Justice Department's concerns were evaluated
and balanced against the views of all the other participating
departments, who "concluded that, on balance, we should go
forward."
</P>
<P>
However, Republicans questioned the president's decision and
vowed to carry out further inquiries. They said a preliminary
review of the 394 documents the White House released raised
troubling questions.
</P>
<P>
"There's no question there were plenty of red flags at the
time," said Representative Christopher Cox, the California
Republican who will head a House select committee examining the
China Issues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0076 </DOCNO>
