<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho's Outgoing PM Casts Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's outgoing Premier
Ntsu Mokhehle cast his last vote as a politician at a polling
station outside the capital Maseru as voting got under way in the
tiny mountain kingdom's third general election Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by his wife Mmaneo, Mokhehle walked into the
polling station just before 10 a.m. They immediately left
afterwards, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The 79-year-old politician, who decided not to contend for the
election because of age and illness, said he cast his vote with a
sense of pride.
</P>
<P>
He said he was happy that the election had been peaceful so
far, and some political parties who threatened earlier to boycott
the poll were participating in the election. He also expressed
satisfaction at the apparent high turnout of voters.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle said it was fitting that he left the political arena
at this point as he did not want to lead the country "too long"
and bore people.
</P>
<P>
"It's boring to be a leader for too long. People tend to get
bored and ultimately revolt against you," said Mokhehle, who
founded the Basotholand Congress Party (BCP) in 1952 and led it
to victory in the 1993 election.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle said he was going to write books about political
liberation movements after retiring.
</P>
<P>
His writings would deal with South Africa's African National
Congress (ANC) and Pan Africanist Congress (PAN), and the BCP and
his newly established Lesotho Congress For Democracy (LCD).
</P>
<P>
About 1.3 million voters are expected to cast their ballots to
select the country's new legislators from more than 400
candidates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
