<HEADLINE> Chinese Pupils to Get UN Environmental Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has announced
that a group of school children living in central and southern
China are to receive the 1998 U.N. environment award owing to
their "outstanding contributions" in the field.
</P>
<P>
The Red Scarf Environment Protection Action Group (RSAG),
formed by pupils in Wangyue Primary School in Changsha, Hunan
Province in 1991, will get the annual "Youth Environment Global
500 Roll" in Moscow on June 5, the World Environment Day.
</P>
<P>
Since the RSAG was set up, its members once a week leave the
school to observe their environment, analyze pollution problems
and propose solutions to the polluters and the government, said
the Nairobi-Based U.N. Environmental Program (UNEP).
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the group discovered that a lot of waste water from a
brewery was being discharged into Xiangjiang River, a tributary
of China's longest Yangtse River, without any treatment.
</P>
<P>
It was at the RSAG's suggestion and under its supervision that
a waste water treatment station was built, said UNEP chief Klaus
Topfer Friday.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, RSAG launched a campaign against so-called white
pollution, which was finally joined by more than 10,000 students
throughout the city, leading to a ban by the local authorities on
the use of all plastic foam dinner sets, he said.
</P>
<P>
The RSAG children have also carried out various activities to
promote environmental education among the young people in the
provincial capital city.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, their school Wangyue, which was established in 1989,
was chosen as an environmental education model by the Environment
Protection Agency of Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
"These environmental defenders have demonstrated that it is at
the community and local level where action to protect the
environment acquires its full meaning," said the UNEP chief.
</P>
<P>
"In honoring them, UNEP hopes that their example will inspire
and guide many other men, women and young people to join the
global coalition dedicated to protecting the environment," he
said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 23 individuals and organizations all over the world
will be awarded by U.N. for their achievements in environment
protection this year.
</P>
<P>
The UNEP launched the Global 500 award in both adult and youth
categories in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
