<HEADLINE> Pakistan Says Indian "Misadventure" to Meet Resolute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said on Saturday that "any misadventure" made by India
would meet a "resolute response," but he reiterated that any
decision would be made in Pakistan's "supreme interests."
</P>
<P>
Sharif was addressing a press briefing here, which was attended
by more than 100 foreign and local reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We have to contend with new realities -- heightened dangers
and an immediate threat (from India) to our security... which may
materialize any moment" ever since India exploded its nuclear
devices on May 11 and 13, he said.
</P>
<P>
But "our nation has arisen to the occasion. There is complete
national consensus to respond to the challenges and threat. This
nation has a history of facing challenges and has never submitted
to threats," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
"Any adventure will be meeting a resolute response," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating that any decision would be in the supreme interests
of the country, Sharif said Pakistan will "behave like a mature
nation."
</P>
<P>
"The whole nation has demonstrated a sober and mature approach
to this complicated situation. We have not behaved in a
tit-for-tat manner. We have not let any madness engulf us," he
said. "Whatever decision we will eventually take it will be in
our supreme national interest."
</P>
<P>
Sharif said Indian nuclear blasts were an attempt to force
Pakistan to abandon its indigenous nuclear program, and to seek a
military solution to the Kashmir problem.
</P>
<P>
He referred to Pakistan's peaceful initiative to hold dialogue
with India to resolve the Kashmir issue in a peaceful manner.
India, however, has "answered it with atomic tests and gone to the
extent of threatening to use nuclear weapons," he said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his disappointment over the reaction of the world
community to the Indian nuclear weaponization, the Pakistani prime
minister said it was a sort of encouragement for New Delhi to
continue its "hegemonistic designs."
</P>
<P>
Talking about his telephone conversation with U.S. President
Bill Clinton, Sharif said he appreciates the concern of world
leaders and hopes that they will stop India from carrying out its
nuclear program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
