Egypt next Tuesday for discussions with Egyptian leaders on
regional issues and a number of bilateral agreements.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by a high-ranking delegation including a number of
his ministers, the Moroccan king will pay a three-day state visit
to Egypt at the invitation of President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will preside over the second session of the
Egyptian-Moroccan Higher Joint Committee meetings, Egypt's
Ambassador to Morocco Amin Ahmed Amin said in an interview with
Voice of Arabs Radio Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The first session of the committee meetings was held in Rabat a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
The committee will deal with ways of fostering economic ties
and a number of agreements will be signed during the forthcoming
session.
</P>
<P>
The final agreement on setting up a joint free trade zone for
furthering bilateral trade will also be endorsed during the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
The joint Egyptian-Moroccan Technical Committee will also
resume talks on the activities of the free trade zone after the
two sides agreed in last July on the broad outlines of the list of
goods and the transitional period of trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade exchange between both sides is "very modest,"
according to Egyptian Minister of Supply and Trade Ahmed
Gowaili. Moroccan imports from Egypt were 15 million U.S. dollars
and Moroccan exports to Egypt stood at 5 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
