<HEADLINE> Two South Africans Starts Final Stages of Qomolangma Ascent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Two South African mountaineers
started the final stages of their attempt to reach the summit of
Mount Qomolangma early Saturday, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
The expedition's general manager, Clare Ellis, said Ian Woodall
and Cathy O'Dowd, together with their Sherpa guides (Tibetan
guides), started their climb to camp three, situated at 8,200
meters above sea level, after high winds on the mountain dropped
slightly.
</P>
<P>
They will start the final assault on the summit from the north,
or the Chinese side, at about 10 p.m. local time (1600 GMT) on
Saturday, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
The two hoped to stand on top of the world's tallest mountain
on Sunday, he said.
</P>
<P>
Success on Qomolangma depends on a short window period when the
jet stream, or high winds that create the familiar plume off the
summit, abate for about two weeks in early May. But the gap this
year has arrived later than normal.
</P>
<P>
In May 1996 Woodall and O'Dowd negotiated the world's tallest
mountain from the south, or Nepalese side, to become the first
South Africans to stand on the Himalayan peak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
