<HEADLINE> Nepal Acts to Forestall Bursting of Glacial Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Efforts have been made to
forestall the possible bursting of the Tsho-Rolpa glacial lake in
the Himalayas, Nepal's official RSS news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The major task now is to siphon by various means the water of
the three-km-long and half-km-wide glacial lake, the largest in
Nepal, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Now the lake is estimated to contain more than 80 million cubic
meters of water.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the excessive pressure of water and earthquakes can
cause the moraine dam to burst. Minor earthquakes have hit
different parts of the country in recent months.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Department of Hydrology and Meteorology
said that works will be carried out to reduce by three meters the
water level of the glacial lake, which is 4,580 meters above sea
level in the Rolwaling Valley, about 80 km east of Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government and some international organizations have
been working together in the past four years to ensure the safety
of residents and property in case the lake bursts, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has installed sirens at 17 places, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Press reports of an imminent bursting of the glacial lake last
summer not only caused panic in the flood-prone areas, but also
caught the attention of the whole country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
