<HEADLINE> Iranian FM Leaves for UAE for Talks on Territorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi left here for the United Arab Emirates (UAE) on Saturday
to explore ways to resolve territorial dispute over three Islands
in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Iranian official news agency IRNA reported that Kharrazi will
discuss bilateral relations and regional developments with UAE
President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan al-Nahyan and Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Sheikh Hamdan bin Zayed al-Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Kharrazi expressed hope that his visit
will open a new chapter in Tehran-Abu Dhabi relationship and will
leave a positive impact on regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He added that there is nothing exceptional about Tehran's
relations with Abu Dhabi in the context of Iran's ties with the
Persian Gulf littoral states.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said during his visit to a number of Arab states in
the region, including the UAE, last November, he was unable to
meet the UAE president "to convey the message of friendship of the
new Iranian administration" because the president was on a trip
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and the UAE were strained because their
dispute over the islands of Abu Musa, the Greater Tunb and the
Lesser Tunb at the mouth of the strategic Hormoz Strait, over
which both Iran and the UAE claimed full sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The UAE called for an international arbitration over the
dispute but Iran claimed that the "misunderstanding" between the
two countries should be solved through mutual talks.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi also praised the statement of Saudi Interior Minister
Prince Nayef Bin Abdul-Aziz that Saudis were behind the 1996
Khobar blast and there has been no Iranian connection, previously
suggested by western media reports, in the case.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi minister Friday ruled out foreign involvement in the
truck bombing of a U.S. military complex in the eastern Saudi town
of Khobar, in which 19 U.S. servicemen were killed.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that from the beginning it was clear that the
issue was an internal one, but those with bad intentions to damage
relations between Iran and Saudi Arabia were at work to implicate
Iran in the blast.
</P>
<P>
The statements coming from Saudi Arabia reflect the realities,
demonstrating the courage and power of the Saudi officials who
have adopted an independent stance despite foreign pressure, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Iran welcomes the recent approach and the resolve of the Saudi
officials and favors further promotion of Tehran-Riyadh
relations, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
The stance of the Saudi interior minister is a sign of firm
decision and political resolve of the Saudi officials to remove
any misunderstanding from public opinion and to boost ties with
Tehran, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
