<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Starts Building New Export Processing Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on
Saturday laid the foundation stone of the country's third export
processing zone (EPZ), in the Mongla sea port, southern
Bangladesh's Bagerhat district, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The setting up of the Mongla EPZ, in the country's second
largest sea port in the hitherto backward southern region, is a
step forward for achieving national prosperity and economic
progress, Hasina said at the foundation-stone laying ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The government believes in balanced development of all regions
in the country, and the EPZs are aimed at alleviating poverty and
achieving economic development of the country through attracting
entrepreneurs from home and abroad and creating more employment
opportunities, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We want to come out of the disgraceful situation of
aid-dependence. Our target is trade, not aid," the prime minister
said.
</P>
<P>
The two exiting EPZs, which are located in Chittagong and Dhaka
respectively, contributed 11 percent to the country's total export
earnings of about 4.4 billion U.S. dollars during the last
financial year ending June 30, 1997, she said.
</P>
<P>
At present, 113 enterprises are in operation in the Chittagong
and Dhaka EPZs, set up in 1983 and 1993 respectively, with an
investment of 293 million dollars and employing some 100,000
workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
