<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Popularity Smashes Political Machinery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Popularity proved to be a decisive
winning factor in the Philippines' May 11 presidential election,
in which a former action movie star leads with a wide margin over
his nine rivals.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Joseph Estrada, a movie star-turned-politician,
has maintained a commanding lead in an unofficial quick count of
the votes conducted by the authoritative National Citizen Movement
for Free Elections (Namfrel).
</P>
<P>
The Namfrel is the sole non-governmental group accredited by
the country's Commission on Elections (Comelec) to conduct the
unofficial quick counting of votes in the national elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest partial results issued by the group,
Estrada of the opposition LAMMP (Fight of Patriotic Filipino
Masses) party garnered 8.24 million votes, 37.1 percent of the
22.2 million votes counted in nearly 80 percent of the total
170,000 precincts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's nearest rival, Speaker of the House of
Representatives Jose de Venecia of the ruling party, gained only
3.24 million votes, 14.6 percent of the votes tallied.
</P>
<P>
Seven of Estrada's nine rivals have conceded defeat and a lot
of his long-time critics, including influential Manila Archbishop
Jaime Sin and the business community, have expressed their
readiness to accept Estrada's presidency.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia himself admitted that Estrada's lead is
insurmountable, but he vowed not to concede until the last vote is
counted.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's runaway victory made a mockery of the ruling
Lakas-NUCD (National Union of Christian Democrats) party's
powerful political machinery and the endorsement of outgoing
President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
The camp of de Venecia had claimed that the speaker would give
the highly popular Estrada a close fight given the ruling party's
clear organizational advantage over the opposition and the strong
support of Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts attributed Estrada's comfortable lead to his
high popularity among the ordinary people, a pervasive discontent
among the masses with the status quo and the ruling party's
breakup caused by the nomination row.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's high popularity among the ordinary people was proved
in an exit poll conducted by the country's most respected
pollster, the Social Weather Station (SWS). The poll showed that
about 52 percent of Estrada's votes were from the middle-lower
classes, or the masses who make up more than 60 percent of the
Philippines' 70 million population.
</P>
<P>
The broad and secure mass support Estrada enjoys is largely
attributed to his movie star background and his populist pro-poor
campaign platform.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who made a household name in the 1960s by playing
Robin Hood-style heroes fighting for the poor, has long been seen
by the masses as "the champion of the poor and defender of the
underdog."
</P>
<P>
Estrada's popularity among the masses has been further
strengthened by his populist pro-poor campaign platform.
</P>
<P>
In his platform, Estrada promises to give priority to
agriculture and food security since the bulk of the population is
engaged in farming and the country has often suffered food
shortages due to the backward agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Estrada's pro-poor platform has been well-received by the
middle-lower classes because they have been waiting too long to
have a larger share of the benefits of economic growth achieved
under the Ramos administration, political analyst John Gilburea
said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has enjoyed rapid economic growth since 1992
thanks to the economic reforms initiated by Ramos. But the
economic growth has failed to improve the life of the lower
classes.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the gap between the poor and the rich has further
widened and the official poverty incidence is still as high as 35
percent, only six percentage points lower than the 1992 level.
</P>
<P>
The regional financial crisis hitting the country last July
added fuel to the flames of dissatisfaction among the poor with
the status quo.
</P>
<P>
"To the masses, Estrada signifies change, while other
presidential candidates personify the establishment or the status
quo," said Gilburea. "To the uneducated, laborers and workers, the
poor and needy, status quo means their continued bondage to
poverty and want."
</P>
<P>
"This pervasive mood for changes subordinates everything, even
the so-called formidable political machine and organization of the
ruling party," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some analysts said, the weakening strength of the
ruling party due to a series of infighting and the poor image of
de Venecia also helped Estrada land at Malacanang, the country's
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
"Even before the election, Lakas had dug its own grave," said
political analyst Amando Doronila. "In endorsing Speaker Jose de
Venecia, President Ramos precipitated the breakup of Lakas, and by
the time the campaign began in February, Lakas was already a
fractured party."
</P>
<P>
Due to the row over Ramos' choice, former presidential economic
adviser Emilio Osmena and former Defense Secretary Renato de
Villa, both close friends of Ramos, bolted the party and competed
for the presidency on their own.
</P>
<P>
The participation of Osmena and de Villa in the presidential
race significantly split the votes for the ruling party, playing
into the hands of Estrada who has a stable constituency among the
masses.
</P>
<P>
What's more, political analysts said, Ramos' choice of de
Venecia was "a hard-sell political product" that is too difficult
for the ruling party and Ramos to make over and promote among the
voters.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia had been lackluster in various pre-election opinion
polls because of his acknowledged image as a "trapo" (Filipino
parlance for the traditional politician good at backroom deals and
fond of staying in power).
</P>
<P>
"De Venecia was too unpopular and a proof of this is that many
Lakas governors won reelection in areas swept by Estrada," said
Doronila.
</P>
<P>
Estrada is now waiting for the proclamation of his victory by
the bicameral congress which will begin the official canvassing of
votes for the president and the vice president next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although Estrada is expected to be another minority president
of the country, yet with an estimated 37-percent win, the ex-movie
star may do better than his predecessor Ramos who got only 23
percent of the votes in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
