<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Use Hyacinth as Fertilizer for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania plans to use
hyacinth, a weed growing rampantly in Lake Victoria which hampers
the free movement of ships, as fertilizer for mushrooms growing.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Commission for Science and Technology (COSTECH)
will pump into the mushroom growing projects one million
shillings (about 1,500 U.S. Dollars), and an equivalent amount
will come from the Zero Emissions Research Initiative (ZERI),
"Daily Mail" said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A seven-man expert team, headed by the Director of the Center
for the Development and Transfer of Technology, a subsidiary of
the COSTECH, S. J. Asman, is making preparations for the
launching of the five projects in Mwanza on Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
The report for the implementation of the projects is expected
to be presented at the Fourth ZERI Congress in Windoek, Namibia
in October, Asman said. ZERI was launched in July 1994 at the
United Nations University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The team is joined by experts from the Ministry of
Agriculture, the Applied Microbiology Unit of the University of
Dar es Salaam, the Mwanza Municipal Council and the
Mikocheni-based Agricultural Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Asman said that a Zimbabwean ZERI expert will soon come to Dar
es Salaam to help implement the projects.
</P>
<P>
The experts have agreed to make use of facilities at the
Mwanza Fisheries Research Institute and a non-governmental
organization which is collecting the water hyacinth in Mwanza.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Task force also agreed that with the help of
non governmental organizations (NGOs), sites for the pilot
projects should be decided and people be trained in cultivating
mushroom, which is in great demand both in Tanzanian and
international markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
