<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little Gender Difference among Chinese Net-Using Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 23 (Xinhua) -- There is little gender difference
in the frequency of using computers and visiting the Internet among
Chinese journalists, according to a symposium, which closed
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium, ``Women Journalists and the 21st Century'',
witnessed the release of a survey on some 1,100 journalists here
earlier this month, which shows that about 90 percent of them are
computer users, and over one quarter of them visit the Internet
regularly.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the journalists use computers and the
Internet to write stories and get information. Only a few
of them conduct interviews, analyze news information and exchange
ideas through the net. There is little gender difference either in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
Bu Wei, an associate research fellow with the Institute of
Journalism and Mass Communications under the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences (CASS), who reported the survey, said that
computers have changed the way of human communication greatly, and
that grasping the computers and the Internet means obtaining power
over getting and releasing information.
</P>
<P>
"Women should catch up with the trend so as not to be left out
in the era of information," she said. "Otherwise, the gender
inequality will worsen.
</P>
<P>
"That is why many researchers care about the proportion
of women Internet users, and is why we conducted the survey," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Bu and her colleagues and journalists from the Capital Women
Journalists Association surveyed some 1,100 journalists from the
"People's Daily", the Xinhua News Agency and the English-language
Newspaper "China Daily", and found that "women and men journalists
occupy the same position in terms of using computers and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
"We may thus be optimistic about the improvement of the present
situation that women account for one third of Chinese
journalists but occupy less than five percent of the leadership
positions in the Chinese mass media," said Chen Chongshan, a
research fellow with CASS's Institute of Journalism and Mass
Communications.
</P>
<P>
Women journalists have become the leading force among Chinese
women Internet-users, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in China women account for only 12
percent of net users, as compared with over 40 percent worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Initiated in May 1995, China's Internet servers serve some
620,000 users of nearly 300,000 computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
