<HEADLINE> Counting Begins As Approval of Peace Deal Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Counting began on Saturday morning
after Friday's referenums in Northern Ireland and the Irish
Republic on the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
As electoral officials in Belfast opened the sealed and audited
ballot boxes containing the people's verdict, an exit poll revealed
Saturday suggested a majority of voters on both sides of the Irish
border had voted for the Northern Ireland peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures from the poll for Ireland's RTE television
showed more than 70 percent of Northern Irish voters had voted
"Yes" in the referendum; while in the Irish Republic, 95 percent of
polled voters had backed the agreement that was reached last month.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is the first time since 1918 that all the people
of Ireland have voted in the same ballot.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcasting Corporation said officials from both
sides of the border had said turnout had been huge, with around 80
percent reported in the North.
</P>
<P>
There was some violence during voting Friday night. Police were
pelted with petrol and paint bombs in Londonderry ans Strabane in
County Tyrone, according to BBC report. Security had been stepped
up throughout the day to guard against potential attacks by
splinter paramilitary groups which oppose the accord.
</P>
<P>
High turnouts in nationalist areas and among first-time voters
and people who did not normally vote had earlier signalled that the
referendum was swinging decisively towards the Yes campaign.
</P>
<P>
But polls showed that the pro-British Protestants were still
divided over the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Northern Ireland will remain in Britain
while building closer ties with Ireland. An assembly will be
established and prisoners of paramilitary groups will be released
within two years.
</P>
<P>
The split among Protestants reflected opposition to the
peace deal's provisions for the early release of prisoners
jailed for their part in three decades of conflict which cost
some 3,600 lives.
</P>
<P>
Final result of the voting will be expected on Saturday
afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Home Minister in Charge of Jammu-Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Indian Home Minister L. K.
Advani, seen as intransigent on the Kashmir issue, has been given
the charge of the department of India-held Jammu and Kashmir
affairs.
</P>
<P>
"The president of India, as advised by the prime minister, has
directed that the prime minister will relinquish the charge of the
department of Jammu and Kashmir affairs and L. K. Advani, minister
of home affairs, will assume charge of the department," said a
communique from the president's office here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to cast a new shadow over the Kashmir issue, the
major dispute between India and Pakistan in the past more than
five decades, after Advani took the charge of the Kashmir affairs.
Advani last week time and again threatened Pakistan regarding the
Kashmir issue. He said here, for instance, on May 18 after a
high-level meeting on Kashmir that Islamabad should realize a
change in the geo-strategic situation in the region and the world
and roll back its anti-India policy, especially with regard to
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
In a sharp reaction to Advani's warning, Pakistan on the same
day said any Indian misadventure would certainly attract a swift
and telling reply.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) issued a strong-worded
statement here Friday fully supporting Advani's stand on the
Kashmir issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
