<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Gurkha Soldiers Demand Increased Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The facilities for former Gurkha
soldiers who served in the British army should be increased in
accordance with a tri-partite agreement reached in 1947 between
Nepal, Britain and India, some Gurkha soldiers said here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers, who were honored with the Victoria Cross, the
highest honor medal of the British army, told a press conference
that they will get their demands fulfilled through diplomatic
channels.
</P>
<P>
A total of 13 Gurkhas won the Victoria Cross (VC) for acts of
bravery during the First and Second World Wars. Six of them have
died.
</P>
<P>
Nepali King Birendra granted an audience on Friday to four of
the VC winners at the Royal Palace, the first time for him to do
so.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with the VC winners on Friday, Nepali Prime
Minister Girija Prasad Koirala said the government would try to
resolve their problem through talks.
</P>
<P>
The demands put forward by the Gurkhas include pension parity
for the retired Gurkhas with their British counterparts, the right
to stay and work in Britain, establishment of a welfare fund for
the children of the Gurkhas and pensions for those dismissed
without pensions.
</P>
<P>
VC winner Captain Ganju Lama said about 250,000 Nepalese
soldiers fought during the First and Second World Wars and 15,000
of them were killed.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 2,500 to 3,000 Nepalese are serving in the British
army, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1947 tri-partite treaty, the British and Indian
armies can recruit the Nepalese, who have been popularly known as
Gurkha soldiers.
</P>
<P>
But the British army drafted the Nepalese already in 1816 under
the Sugauli Treaty signed between Nepal and the East India Company
of Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0137 </DOCNO>
