<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for More Malaysian Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 23 (Xinhua) -- After the U.S. waived sanctions upon
foreign companies doing big business with Iran, Tehran encouraged
Malaysia to be more active in economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Majlis Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri Saturday told his
Malaysian counterpart that Malaysia can be enganged in more
development projects in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Malaysia, France and Russia had signed a
contract totaling 2 billion U.S. dollars with Iran to tap a gas
field in the Persian Gulf before the U.S. threatened sanctions
against them under a domestic law designed to isolate
Iran. Washington called off the threats early this week in strong
international opposition.
</P>
<P>
Nouri made the remarks when seeing off the Malaysian House of
Representatives Speaker Muhammad Zahir Ismail at the airport after
his week-long visit to Tehran, the Iranian official news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Ismail termed his talks with Iranian
officials as "productive," expressing the hope that his visit
would further bring the outlooks of Iran and Malaysia closer.
</P>
<P>
Nouri said high-level changes can play an effective role in
coordinating the viewpoints of the two countries in their
decision-makings at international forums.
</P>
<P>
Praising Malaysian stances at regional and international
meetings for the benefit of Islam and the world of Islam, Nouri
said Iran is willing to boost ties and increase joint investment
with Malaysia. 
</P>
