<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Hopes to Talk with EU on Fish Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government has
reiterated its wish to hold dialog with the European Union (EU)
so as to compel the EU to cancel its ban on Mozambican fish
exports announced at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi disclosed this here
Friday, saying, "We should conduct constructive dialogs" in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
A cholera epidemic broke out in Mozambique last August. The
European Union announced to ban imports of Mozambican fish
products at the end of 1997, claiming the products did not meet
hygienic standards and might spread cholera to Europe.
</P>
<P>
According to Mocumbi, the World Health Organizations (WHO) has
checked on the fishing and freezing process in Mozambique, saying
it is unfair for the EU to cease fish imports from the country
citing the issue of cholera.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique harvests about 8,000 tons of prawns and over 10,000
tons of fish annually, with its export market mainly projected to
Europe. The EU ban on the country's sea products has resulted in
a reported loss of 240 million U.S. Dollars so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
