<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record US Travelers Expected During Memorial Day Vacation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 32 million Americans
were expected to take to the skies and highways during this
Memorial Day vocation starting Friday through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Friday was the busiest day in U.S. aviation history and return
flights Tuesday will be busy as well, the Air Transport
Association (ATA) said.
</P>
<P>
Overall travel should edge up one percent from last year's
Memorial Day weekend, with 26.7 million people expected to travel
more than 100 miles from home by car, and 5.4 million by air,
train or bus, the American Automobile Association said.
</P>
<P>
The Memorial Day, now officially observed on the last Monday in
May, has been set aside in most states of the United States for
observances in memory of dead members of the armed forces of all
wars. People usually travel during the three-day holiday weekend
before the Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
The ATA expected 12.5 million flight boardings over the weekend
while San Francisco International Airport warned passengers to
leave their cars at home as parking lots filled up early.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Ron Wilson said the airport handled about 120,000
passengers Friday -- its busiest day since opening in 1926.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that a robust economy and low fuel prices are the
major factors that spur record American travelers to jam highways
and airports.
</P>
<P>
Travel industry officials warned vacationers to anticipate
crowds and delays.
</P>
<P>
"Things are going to be crowded and there are going to be
lines. I think a majority of people going places this weekend
recognize that this is going to be one of the busiest weekends
ever, a weekend to rival the busiest Thanksgiving," said James
Ashurst, spokesman for the American Society of Travel Agents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
