<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Okays $3.9 Million for ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States has agreed to
provide 3.9 million U.S. Dollars to help the Nigerian-led west
African peace keeping force ECOMOG to check rebel atrocities
against civilians in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"Due to the large inflow of refugees from Sierra Leone and
rebel atrocities against innocent civilians, the U.S. State
Department has approved the immediate provision of 3.9 million
Dollars as assistance for ECOMOG operations," the Daily Times
Saturday quoted a report reaching here as saying.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG drove the military junta out of the capital Freetown in
mid-February for the reinstatement of the legitimate government
of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, ousted in a coup last May.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force has since claimed control of all the
district capitals in Sierra Leone while remnants of the junta
forces and allied rebels fled to the north and east to engage in
a guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
However, ECOMOG and allies have been unable to stem a campaign
of terror waged by the junta remnants and rebel allies, who have
recently been killing and maiming civilians mainly in the north,
leaving hundreds of civilians mutilated.
</P>
<P>
Many local villagers have fled to neighboring Guinea to keep
off the atrocities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
