<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Wins Satellite Telecommunication Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Motorola has been chosen to
replace Boeing as the lead builder of an ambitious billion-dollar
satellite telecommunications project.
</P>
<P>
Teledesic, the "Internet-in-the-sky" project, plans to launch
288 satellites in low earth orbit to provide high-speed Internet
access, video, voice and digital services from modern cities to
villages worldwide.
</P>
<P>
It has been among the most watched satellite projects since the
cellular pioneer Craig McCaw and Microsoft chairman Bill Gates
announced their plans in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Boeing was hired last year to lead the project expected to cost
at least 9 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Boeing will remain a partner, promising to complete its
investment of 100 million dollars. The company reportedly had
disputes over the project's cost.
</P>
<P>
A key reason for picking Motorola is its experience in building
the Iridium system, a network of 66 satellites that will offer
cellular-telephone service around the world.
</P>
<P>
Motorola, now as Teledesic's partner, will abandon its own
plans for Celestri, another high-speed computer system targeted at
Teledesic's market.
</P>
<P>
The company is investing 750 million dollars in cash and
technology for the Celestri project.
</P>
<P>
Teledesic's plans are considered the most ambitious of several
communications-satellite projects, requiring the integration of
advanced space and communications technology, while trying to
mass-produce satellites at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
Gates and McCaw still each own significant portions of
Teledesic. Saudi Prince Alwaleed Bin Talal, a wealthy individual
businessman, invested 200 million dollars in the project last
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Begin in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Basotho people
braved the chilly morning weather Saturday to queue for the
mountain kingdom's third democratic general elections since its
independence in 1966.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations opened at 7 a.m. and will close at 5 p.m,
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
At the Phetahatso Medium School in Mohalalitoe near capital
Maseru -- one of the more than 2,000 polling stations countrywide
-- about 1,000 people were on the queue by 5.30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
They had made a fire to ward off the cold weather while
election officials inside the polling station enjoyed warmth from
a heater.
</P>
<P>
Twelve political parties and 31 independent candidates will be
participating in the legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
There were speculations that the opposition Basotho National
Party (BNP), which ruled Lesotho for the first two decades of its
independence, would win the polls in the tiny and often
politically troubled kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Although no formal opinion surveys have been done, indirect
indications, such as turnout at elections rallies, suggested that
the BNP will win, a South African media report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
