<HEADLINE> Cotton Prices Surge on Dry Weather Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Cotton prices increased sharply
Friday for fear of dry weather in the high plains of Texas, said
reports reaching here from the New York Cotton Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The cotton for July delivery settled 1.41 cents higher at 67.99
cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
The main reason behind the increase, analysts say, is the dry
weather fear. 1.4 million acres of non-irrigated cotton land near
Lubbock, Texas, has had very little rain this month and the
forecast is not promising.
</P>
<P>
Farmers will start planting in the next 10 days whether there
will be rain or not, but the forecast gives a little hope for rain
in the next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
