<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Regional Sports Policy Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Vice-President Simon
Muzenda has called on SADC countries to set up a regional
physical education, sport and recreation policy to be preceded by
national policies in various member states.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda said such policies must include specific sport
development in schools as well as programs for out-of-school
youths, The Herald reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sports development aimed at young people in primary and
secondary schools should be the backbone of sports development in
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and all 14
member states should ensure that women sports programs were given
adequate resources, Muzenda said.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing a meeting of ministers of culture,
information and sport which ended in Harare Friday.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda also called on the SADC countries to enact laws that
prevent copyrights and effective piracy control to promote viable
cultural industries.
</P>
<P>
The vice president also urged the media to be objective when
reporting sports and cultural issues.
</P>
<P>
"I urged the press to report extensively about cultural news
from the Southern African Development Community member states and
other regions in Africa," he said, adding, "this will enable our
people to feel that they are able to free themselves from bondage
of underdevelopment in terms of culture."
</P>
<P>
"At the moment too much emphasis is being put on covering what
is happening in Europe and America," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Paulo Muchanga, chairman of the Committee of Ministers of
Culture, Information and Sport and Mozambican Minister of
Culture, Information and Sport, said the meeting was aimed at
fostering regional integration and strengthening the region's
resolve to work together toward a common future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
