<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Blames Weather for Gloomy Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Both drought and the El Nino rains
are to blame for stopping economic recovery in Kenya, Minister
for Planning and National Development George Saitoti has said.
</P>
<P>
The first half of last year was characterized by drought while
the end of the year was affected by the El Nino rains, he was
quoted Saturday by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Another setback is heavy spending on the general election held
at the end of last year, the minister said in the report named
"1998 Economic Survey" issued Friday.
</P>
<P>
Together they reduced the growth in gross domestic product
(GDP) to only 2.3 percent against a projected growth of five
percent, disrupting the economic recovery starting in 1994, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He reported a fall in all the key sectors of the economy, led
by agriculture and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Farmers bought 14 percent less fertilizer and other chemicals,
and grew less food which caused famine in some areas, forcing the
government to declare disaster zones.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from tourism fell by 11.6 percent. The industry was
depressed in terms of both tourist arrivals, hotel occupancy,
game park entries and income generated.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing, building and transport recorded significant
drops as a result of the collapse of the infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The value of manufacturing output grew by 1.9 percent compared
to 3.7 percent in 1996, but due to a reduction in import duties
and improved performance by the Export Processing Zones and the
expanding regional market, the sector was cushioned.
</P>
<P>
The poor state of the roads led to increased costs for the
transport industry where output fell to 5.2 percent last year
from 14.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Areas that recorded growth were banking, pipeline transport,
the media and capitalization of the Nairobi Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Information and media activities recorded commendable
performance following increased sales of radios and television
sets.
</P>
<P>
Market capitalization based on the number of shares and the
prevailing market price increased from 98 million Shillings
(about 1.75 million U.S. Dollars) in 1996 to 114 million
Shillings (1.9 million Dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On internal trade, Saitoti said the overall balance of payment
deteriorated. While import volumes rose, exports stagnated,
resulting in a current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
However, he projected a marginally higher growth rate for
1998, saying the government will maintain a tight fiscal policy
to achieve a reduced budget deficit. The new budget will be
issued on June 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
