<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesians Start Returning Home From Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Only two days after Indonesia's
new president was sworn in, flights to Jakarta were mostly full as
Singapore hotel guests escaping Indonesia's violence were checking
out to return, travel industry sources confirmed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
With Sunday's flights to Jakarta already packed, travel agents
said that the trend is extending further into next week.
</P>
<P>
"The next available seats are on Wednesday," a ticket agent for
Garuda, an Indonesia airlines, was quoted by local television as
saying. Basically, people are slowly starting to go back, a hotel
manager observed.
</P>
<P>
Singapore hotels experienced an unexpected boom in business in
mid-May when thousands of expatriates and ethnic Chinese
Indonesians fled violence in various cities in Indonesia,
particularly the capital city of Jakarta. The violence was
reported to have left more than 500 dead.
</P>
<P>
The exodus during the turmoil sent Singapore hotels occupancy
rates increasing to between 90 to 100 percent, well above the
average earlier in the year. Now some hotel managers are expecting
occupancy rates at their hotels to gradually fall back to around
70 percent, or even lower.
</P>
<P>
While some of the ethnic Chinese Indonesians who fled were
returning to Indonesia, some others said they were checking out
from hotels to look for apartments in Singapore to stay longer,
one hotel manager said.
</P>
<P>
As for expatriates who were leaving, not everyone is heading
back to Indonesia. It was said only the breadwinners were
returning to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Besides, according to a television report, many of those
expatriates who were returning to Indonesia had tickets to
Singapore in case violence re-erupts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rolls-Royce Forms Third Joint Venture in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Rolls-Royce plc, a leading power
systems company, recently announced it will set up a new joint
venture in China to manufacture electrical protection and control
systems and products.
</P>
<P>
The Baoding Tianwei Reyrolle Limited, which is the third joint
venture of Rolls-Royce in China, will be 55 percent owned by
Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
The remaining share is controlled by Baoding Tianwei Group
Co. Ltd. located in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
According to Stan Jones, managing director of transmission and
distribution for Rolls-Royce, the joint venture will utilize an
exiting factory owned by Baoding Tianwei Group. Production will
start in 1999 with further products to follow.
</P>
<P>
This is the second operation of the transmission and
distribution division of Rolls-Royce in China. The first, Fushun
Reyrolle Bushing Company in northeast China's Liaoning Province,
is already operational.
</P>
<P>
Rolls-Royce also has a joint venture with Xi'an Aero Engine
Corp. in northwest China's Shaanxi Province. It manufactures
components for Rolls-Royce engines.
</P>
<P>
The first delivery of components came 10 months after the new
factory broke ground. And the products are to be assembled in the
United Kingdom where Rolls-Royce headquarters is.
</P>
<P>
The engine powers Fokker 100, Gulfstream IV and re-engined
Boeing 727-100.
</P>
<P>
Jones predicted the sales volume of this business will be 22
million US dollars in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
