<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudis Behind U.S. Base Blast: Saudi Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's interior
minister has ruled out foreign involvement in a 1996 bombing that
killed 19 U.S. servicemen, saying Saudis were behind the incident,
Saudi newspaper Arab Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The bombing "took place at Saudi hands," the minister, Prince
Nayef Bin Abdul-Aziz, was quoted as telling a group of Kuwaiti
newspaper editors visiting the kingdom headed by Kuwaiti
Information Minister Yousef Mohammad Al-Sumait Friday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believed that this statement is apparently aimed at
ruling out Iranian involvement, previously suggested by western
media reports, in the truck bombing of a U.S. military complex in
the eastern Saudi town of Khobar two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The minister's comments could boost Saudi and U.S. efforts
towards improving ties with regional heavyweight Iran after years
of tension, they said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Saudi Arabia have been improving
since Mohammad Khatami became Iran's president last August. There
have also been signs of improvement in relations between Iran and
the U.S..
</P>
<P>
At the end of March, Nayef said Saudi authorities would
announce the results of the Khobar bombing once the probe was
completed, but Saudi Arabia refused to implicate Iran in the
blast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
