<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Endorsed as Member of ASEAN Regional Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF), the
political and security forum of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN), is likely to absorb Mongolia as a new member, the
Philippine News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Philippine Foreign Affairs Undersecretary
Lauro Baja, who chaired the just-concluded two-day ARF Senior
Officials Meeting here, as saying they had endorsed the admission
of Mongolia into the forum.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed to recommend the admission of Mongolia into the ARF.
The ARF foreign ministers will make the final decision when they
meet in Manila next July," Baja said.
</P>
<P>
Baja said the decision to endorse Mongolia's bid to join the
ARF is consonant with the forum's desire to concentrate on
countries within the ARF's geographic footprint.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Mongolia formally applied to join the ARF
when its foreign minister visited the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The ARF groups the nine ASEAN members, namely Brunei,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Thailand,
Singapore and Vietnam, and their dialogue partners including
Australia, Canada, China, Japan, India, South Korea, New Zealand,
Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Two other countries, Cambodia and Papua New Guinea, enjoy
observer status in the forum. Cambodia will be formally integrated
into the ARF once it is officially admitted into the ASEAN, most
likely before the year ends, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines currently chairs the ASEAN, and in the same
capacity, will chair this year's ARF Foreign Ministerial Meeting
scheduled to be held here from July 27 to 29 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
