<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Promises to Join Treaty Banning Land Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States Friday
promised to join the international treaty banning land mines by
2006, but determined to develop alternate weapons.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced at a Friday concluded international
conference on land mines convened by the State Department.
</P>
<P>
It said it would destroy by 1999 all non-self destructing
anti-personnel land mines, except for those needed for South
Korea. The U.S. will end the use of all such land mines outside
South Korea by 2003, including those that self-destruct.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. will aggressively pursue the objective of
having alternatives to anti-personnel land mines ready for South
Korea by 2006, including those that self-destruct. It will also
search aggressively for alternatives to mixed anti-tank systems.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Pentagon has no fielded alternatives to land
mines at present, but it has requested 4.7 million U.S. dollars in
the fiscal 1999 budget to search for them.
</P>
<P>
The Associated Press said in a report that one possibility was
a weapon that would temporarily disable an approaching enemy, but
not kill. Another involves sensors that warn of an opponent's
approach and then trigger weapon systems.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had previously refused to sign the treaty banning land
mines, claiming that such weapons are needed on the Korean
peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai AD Agencies Hard Hit by Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's advertising industry has
been hard hit by the economic crisis as nearly 10 percent of the
employees have lost their jobs and many local agencies have ceased
operations or downsized, the Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Local agencies have closed down after failing to attract
clients or foreign partners, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
According to the estimation of Witawat Jayapani, a senior
director of Ogilvy + Mather (Thailand) LTD, one of Thailand's
largest advertising agencies, there were about 10,000 people in
the local industry in more than 200 advertising companies.
</P>
<P>
Advertising companies in Thailand are facing difficulties as
local corporate clients have cut their advertising spending by
over 40 percent in response to the economic slump.
</P>
<P>
Local advertising agents said forming an alliance with foreign
advertising firms is now the solution for local agencies to
survive.
</P>
<P>
Among the major benefits enjoyed by local agencies forming an
alliance with foreign partners is the acquisition of
multi-national clients as well as access to international
resources and information, they said.
</P>
<P>
Witawat also suggested small and medium-sized agencies lift
their client service standards to survive, while big firms make
their prices more competitive when maintaining high standards of
service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
