<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 22 (Xinhua) -- There are some 40 million
children at a world level who live in deplorable conditions in the
streets, the non-government organization Free the Children said
Friday in Monterrey, north Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Craigh Kielburger, the founder of the organization, said in a
press communique that of the total, some 250,000 minors are forced
to work in conditions of abuse and bondage.
</P>
<P>
Kielburger asked young people to commit themselves to the
struggle for the rights and freedom of the children of the street.
</P>
<P>
He urged adult people to respect in a responsible manner the
rights of the minors who work in the streets.
</P>
<P>
Mexico signed an international agreement in 1990 for the
defense of the rights of the children, together with other 95
countries of the world, which must be complied with, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kielburger said that in developing countries such as Haiti or
Brazil, children, who are only four years old and learn to work,
are often lashed and carry machetes longer than themselves.
</P>
<P>
Some 110,000 Mexican children perform some kind of work in the
streets to contribute to the living of their families, according
to the National System for the Integral Development of the Family
(DIF) of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The figure was obtained from a study jointly made with the
United Nations Organization for the Children (UNICEF), DIF General
Director Mario Fuentes Alcala said during a working tour of the
states located in the Yucatan Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The official explained that the DIF created programs of social
assistance which help the parents of the children to land a job
and improve the living conditions of the family.
</P>
<P>
Another important program applied by the DIF for the
development of the Mexican children is that of school lunches.
</P>
<P>
This program is applied in Chiapas, Oaxaca, Guerrero and
Yucatan states, which suffer high levels of malnutrition in
children population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
