<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to See 20,000 Lose Jobs This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 23 (Xinhua) -- A total of 20,000 Singapore
workers could lose their jobs this year as the regional financial
crisis runs its course, said National Trades Union Congress (NTUC)
chief and Minister without Portfolio Lim Boon Heng.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times reported Saturday that Lim told local Radio
Heart on Friday night that about 7,000 workers had been laid off
in the first quarter of this year alone, marking the highest
figure on record.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that indications so far seemed to suggest that
the figure for the second quarter would be "equally high."
</P>
<P>
"This is because of the effects of the currency turmoil in the
region. It has not yet stabilized," he said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that what happened in the past few months will
really bite in the second half of this year. And unfortunately, he
said, the prospects would be for more retrenchments to come.
</P>
<P>
"We should expect that this year, the total number of jobs lost
through retrenchment will top 20,000," double the figure for last
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that those who had lost their jobs might not
be able to find new jobs easily, even though 17,100 jobs had been
created in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, was because three-quarters of those retrenched
were manufacturing workers, whereas half of the new jobs were in
the construction industry, an area shunned by Singaporeans. The
other 4,000 new jobs were in financial services.
</P>
<P>
"So, clearly, there is a job mismatch. Manufacturing workers
cannot fit into the financial sector easily without a lot of
re-training," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
To stay employed, workers might have little choice but to take
up jobs which they had been unwilling to previously, such as
construction work, he pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
