<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast European Nations Agree on Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Seven Southeastern European
countries signed here Friday a letter of intent on establishing a
multinational peacekeeping force in the region.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed at a deputy defense ministerial meeting
of seven participating countries -- Albania, Bulgaria, Macedonia,
Greece, Italy, Romania and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The proposed force, a brigade 2,000 to 3,000 strong, will be
available for conflict prevention and other peacekeeping
operations under NATO or the Western European Union command with
the mandate of the United Nations or the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The document decided to create a standing headquarters, with a
rotating post of commander, for the brigade.
</P>
<P>
Joint exercises of troops from participating countries will be
held when necessary, the document said.
</P>
<P>
The document said the force is not aimed against any other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Friday's meeting also decided to promote exchanges of
information, visits of small military units and commanding
institutions and cooperation in other fields among the
participating countries within the framework of peaceful
partnership for peace.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from two observer countries -- the United States and
Slovenia -- and NATO and the OSCE also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Franklin Kramer, assistant secretary of defense of the United
States, said in a joint news conference after the meeting that the
force will not be deployed in Kosovo, the troubled province of the
Republic of Serbia in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The force was first proposed by Albania in October 1996 and
officially discussed in the Southeastern European defense
ministerial meeting held in Sofia, Bulgaria, last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
