<HEADLINE> Russian Authorities to Prosecute Gunmen in Dagestan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian Interior Minister Sergei
Stepashin warned Friday that those responsible for inciting the
riots in Makhachkala, capital of Dagestan, would be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
After attending a Dagestani National Council (local parliament)
meeting, Stepashin told reporters that he had had a talk with
Nadirshakh Khachilayev, a member of the Russian Duma and head of
Russia's Muslim Union, whose supporters Wednesday and Thursday
clashed with local police and seized the main government building
in Makhachkala.
</P>
<P>
Two policemen were killed and several others injured in the
clashes.
</P>
<P>
After several hours of negotiations, the Dagestani leadership
reached a deal with the gunmen. The rioters, afterward, withdrew
from the government building and Lenin Square was under police
control.
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin moved quickly to try to defuse the crisis.
President Boris Yeltsin set up an emergency headquarters and asked
Stepashin, the interior minister, to cut short his Germany tour
and return to Moscow to take care of the incident.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, who arrived in Makhachkala before dawn Friday, said
that Khachilayev has promised to try all efforts to prevent such a
rioting from occurring again.
</P>
<P>
Magomed Ali Magomedov, speaker of the Dagestani National
Council, said the Makhachkala incident was a "rebellion," which
brought Dagestan to the verge of a civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported Dagestani interior minister,
Magomed Abdurazakov, stepped down Friday and was replaced by
another ministry official, Adilgerey Magomedtagirov.
</P>
<P>
Dagestan, a mainly Moslem republic, lies between Chechnya and
the Caspian Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
