<HEADLINE> Italian Minister Defends Abortion Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Italy's 1978 law legalizing abortion
has not led to a growth in abortions, Italian Social Affairs
Minister Livia Turco said in defense of the law on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The law, known as Law 194, was passed exactly 20 years ago.
Anti-abortion groups took the opportunity of Friday's anniversary
to stage protests demanding that the law be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
Turco told reporters that "in the last 20 years, there has been
a dramatic and constant fall in the number of abortions."
</P>
<P>
"The law hasn't led to an increase in the number of abortions
because abortion has always existed. Obviously, a lot remains to
be done because abortion is still a traumatic experience for a
woman," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We should calculate the number of abortions carried out before
1978 and the number of women who died having illegal ones. Our
society is a lot more advanced today. I believe that the problem
of life needs to be discussed on another level."
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that modifying the abortion law is the road to
pursue. Rather, we should be trying to help women who desire to be
mothers but find that they simply can't afford to have a child,"
Turco said.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show a steady decline in the number of
legal abortions, from 235,000 in 1982 to 129,000 in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
