<HEADLINE> Serbia, Kosovo Agree to Hold Weekly Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian government and ethnic
Albanian representatives from Kosovo province agreed Friday to
meet and talk on a weekly basis in a mutual effort to defuse
tension in the riot-stricken Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The deal was struck at a meeting between Ratko Markovic, deputy
premier of Serbia, and Pehmi Agani, an advisor to the ethnic
Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, the Tangjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
A press release from provincial government of Kosovo said
the meeting was conducted in a tolerating and frank atmosphere and
featured by discussions on how to organize and proceed with future
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the Kosovo issue can be solved
peacefully only when the resolution is based on equality for all
citizens and ethnic groups, mutual respect, tolerance and
non-violence.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic met Rugova on May 15 and
agreed to begin peaceful talks following mediation by the
U.S. special envoys Richard Holbrooke and Robert Gelbard.
</P>
<P>
Local observers cautioned that due to great difference in the
stance of the two sides on the final resolution, the way to peace
will be arduous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
