<HEADLINE> U.S. Judge Orders Secret Service Employees to Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. federal judge Friday
ordered three Secret Service employees to testify before a grand
jury investigating an alleged affair involving President Bill
Clinton and former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
In her ruling, U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson
rejected the Secret Service's contention that its agents deserved
a special "protective function privilege" to avoid testifying for
fear that they would lose the confidence of the president if they
revealed what they observed.
</P>
<P>
She dismissed the administration's arguments that compelling
testimony could result in agents being kept farther from the
president, heightening the likelihood of assassination.
</P>
<P>
Her ruling granted Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr's motion
to compel two uniformed Secret Service officers and an agency
counsel to appear before the grand jury investigating the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
The administration still can appeal or change its legal
strategy to try to stop the agents from testifying.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton, talking with reporters in the Rose Garden,
said of the ruling, "At least, it will have a chilling effect
perhaps on the conversations presidents have and the work that
they do and the way they do it," according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not know if the Secret Service would appeal the
ruling. "I don't know because I'm not involved," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department and Secret Service said in a statement
that they were reviewing the decision and "continue to believe
that any action that could distance the Secret Service from the
president increases the danger to his life and that of future
presidents." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
