<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Says Interest Rates Cut will Help Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 23 (Xinhua) -- China should lower the real
interest rates to achieve its target of 8 percent GDP growth this
year, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
There is still room for further interest rate cuts, and high
real interest rates are the key reason for China's ever-declining
gross domestic product growth, today's China Daily quoted a
Chinese official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Xiao, an official with the State Economic and Trade
Commission, told the newspaper that real interest has kept rising
with inflation going downward since 1994.
</P>
<P>
He said that the real interest rate for a one-year loan
computed on the basis of the retail price index, increased by 16
percentage points from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the real interest rate has surged up more than 20
percentage points since 1993 if computed on the basis of
producers' price index.
</P>
<P>
"Such high real interest rates mean substantial consumption and
borrowing costs for both households and firms," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
He said that appropriate interest rate cuts will not affect the
stability of exchange rates because the renminbi yuan has been
under a certain pressure of appreciation as a result of sustained
net trade surpluses even amidst the financial crisis in East and
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The official's view was also echoed by Song Guoqing, a Chinese
economist in Beijing University, who claimed that the nominal
interest rate can still be adjusted downward one or two percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
But the central government seems to lean more towards
increasing fiscal spending, another option for stimulating the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said that the central
government is ready to move 750 billion US dollars into
infrastructure building in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rate should be of higher priority,
considering the declining GDP growth, Zhao said, who believed
further interest rate cuts seem to be necessary and possible as
well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Japan Discuss Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Japan have discussed new
ways to promote bilateral economic cooperation, official newspaper
The New Light of Myanmar reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day second meeting of Myanmar-Japan bilateral economic
cooperation, which ended here Friday, focused on bilateral trade
and Japan's investment in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by Myanmar minister at the Office of
the Chairman of the State Peace and Development Council
Brigadier-General Able, Chairman of Japan-Myanmar Economic
Committee Iwao Toriumi and Japanese Ambassador Kazuo Asaka as well
as businessmen of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, chambers of commerce and industry of
Myanmar and Japan reached an agreement on the establishment of an
economic cooperation committee between the two sides to enhance
the economic cooperation of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Japan had injected over 206
million U.S. dollars in 17 permitted projects in Myanmar by the
end of April this year, ranking the ninth in 23 countries or
regions which invested a total of 7 billion dollars in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Japan, one of the major donors of Myanmar, has extended
grant-in-aid for debt relief to the country for 19 times. The
latest aid provided in February this year was 2 billion yen (16
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan has also provided Myanmar with grant aid of
over 500,000 dollars since last November to help implement
agriculture, health and rural community development projects in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
