<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Pleased with EU-U.S. Sanction Compromise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Italy is pleased with the compromise
deal between the European Union and the United States that eases
restrictions on European businesses investing in Cuba, Iran and
Libya, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dini said at a cabinet meeting that the compromise, reached at
the EU-U.S. summit in London last Monday, was the result of "a
very firm and determined" intervention on the part of Europe, and
that Italy, too, was gathering the "fruit of its own lengthy
efforts" against the U.S. sanctions, the Italian news agency ANSA
reported.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the U.S. Helms-Burton and D'Amato laws, which
penalizes European firms trading with Cuba, Iran and Libya, had
been "hotly contested" by the EU and had threatened to blight
economic relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Dini noted that it was Italy's insistence that pushed the
U.S. to include Libya in the compromise agreement, which was at
first applicable only to Iran and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the EU agreed to a series of restrictions on
high-technology and military exports to Iran and Libya while the
U.S. agreed to waive the Iran-Libya Sanctions Act (also known as
the D'Amato law) and renounce sanctions against European companies
investing in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As for Cuba, the EU committed itself to not investing in
U.S. property confiscated by Cuba after the 1959 revolution and to
avoiding exports deemed contrary to U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
In return, the U.S. agreed to waive sanctions provided by the
Helms-Burton Law, which penalizes foreign firms investing in Cuban
property seized after the revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980523.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
