<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Launch Campaign to Conserve Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Public Health Ministry
will launch a campaign on World Environment Day on June 5, in
which the public will be asked to help conserve 11 of the
country's rivers, including Chao Phraya river, according to Public
Health Permanent Secretary Prakrom Vuthipongse.
</P>
<P>
If nothing is done to prevent further deterioration, there
could be a shortage of water and this would affect households, the
Bangkok Post Saturday quoted Prakrom as saying.
</P>
<P>
Prakrom said community leaders, students, private sector firms,
and the state authorities would be urged to take joint
responsibility in cleaning up the rivers.
</P>
<P>
The quality of the Chao Phraya river is of most concern in
Bangkok because pollutants are continuously discarded into the
water.
</P>
<P>
The level of oxygen dissolved in the water is only 1-2
milligrams per liter, which means that the river water can be used
only for navigation. 
</P>
