<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Suggests Unifying Three Rome-Based U.N. Organizations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro
suggested Friday that three Rome-based United Nations
organizations be merged into one central unit.
</P>
<P>
The three organizations the president talked about are the Food
and Agriculture Organization (FAO), the World Food Program (WFP)
and the International Fund for Agricultural Development (FAD).
</P>
<P>
In an address at the inauguration of the new WFP headquarters,
Scalfaro said his proposal was not only a logistical question, but
also a concrete demonstration of rationalizing the synergies of
these organizations while, at the same time, maintaining their
specific roles and targets.
</P>
<P>
The three organizations share the same goal for food security
and agricultural development, Scalfaro said, adding that after
merger they would see their clout grow within the United Nations
and the general costs reduced in view of already limited resources.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of the WFP's efforts and abilities in handling
both emergencies and development, Scalfaro said, "the time has
come for actions more oriented toward prevention which work in a
structural way to ensure the continuity of available food."
</P>
<P>
The Italian head of state went on to stress the need to
modernize and make efforts more professional because "famine is a
vicious circle, humanity's greatest inhumanity."
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at today's inauguration were WFP Executive
Director Catherine Bertini and FAO Director Jacques Diouf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
