<HEADLINE> Brazilian Exports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, May 22 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian exports increased
7.7 percent in the first four months of this year compared to the
same period of 1997, reaching 16.473 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Industry, Commerce, and Tourism Ministry,
published Friday by the press, showed that imports were 18.213
billion dollars during the January-April period, a reduction of
two percent from the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade registered a deficit of 1.74 billion dollars,
against the 3.7 billion dollars registered in the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
The sale of manufactured goods alone accumulated an income of
9.625 billion dollars, with an increase of more than 16 percent
over the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that that the country lost ground in the
agriculture area. The income from exports was being affected by a
low price of agriculture products in the international market, it
added.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, Brazilian soy beans and coffee
exports registered a reduction of 13.3 percent in value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
