<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Expands Vaccination Against Germ Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen told the U.S. military on Friday to vaccinate all 2.4
million members of the armed forces against the deadly disease
anthrax.
</P>
<P>
Cohen approved a pilot anthrax vaccination program for troops
deployed in the Gulf area last December at a time when military
action against Iraq might have been imminent.
</P>
<P>
Since the Gulf War in 1991, the U.S. military has built up a
stockpile of more than six million doses. President Bill Clinton
on Friday called for stockpiling vaccines against biological
weapons attack.
</P>
<P>
"All conditions for implementing the anthrax vaccination
program have now been met," the Pentagon said in a statement,
quoting Cohen.
</P>
<P>
Anthrax is usually an animal disease but it can infect humans
and is 99 percent lethal to unprotected individuals.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said servicemen and women will take a series of
six inoculations over an 18-month period, followed by an annual
booster.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also announced on Friday plans to station specially
trained "rapid assessment" teams in 10 states for responding to
weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
