<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tangshan Offers More Preferential Terms to Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Tangshan, a northern Chinese
city reborn from a devastating earthquake in 1976, will provide
overseas investors with more preferential treatment, Mayor Zhang
He announced at the Hebei Provincial Trade Fair, which closed here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Income tax will be cut to be 24 percent for production
enterprises funded by overseas investors, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises which engage in agriculture, forestry or animal
husbandry, or are located in underdeveloped areas will enjoy
income tax reductions ranging from 15 to 30 percent as from their
11th year of operation, after the exemption or reduction of taxes
for the first 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented foreign-funded firms will have tax rebates
executed at a stroke on their export custom declaration forms.
</P>
<P>
Tangshan, a century-old industrial center in Hebei Province,
was razed by an earthquake on July 28, 1976. After two decades of
construction a modernized city appeared.
</P>
<P>
Investors from 38 countries and regions have set up 357
enterprises in Tangshan, bringing in investment totalling 1.1
billion US dollars. Most of these firms are making profits.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
