<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Calls for Solidarity with Colonial Peoples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Friday that despite success in de-colonization,
there is still work to do in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a statement to the U.N. Special
Committee on de-colonization which met this morning to observe the
Week of Solidarity with the Peoples of All Colonial Territories
Fighting for Freedom, Independence and Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
In the 38 years since the adoption of the Declaration on the
Granting of Independence to Colonial Countries and Peoples, some
60 former colonial territories inhabited by over 80 million people
have attained independence and joined the United Nations as
sovereign states, but the work for de-colonization remains
unfinished, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As we reach the final year of the International Decade for the
Eradication of Colonialism, we must redouble our efforts and see
this process to its conclusion," he added.
</P>
<P>
There are still 17 Non-Self-Governing Territories in the world
and the U.N. has been observing the Week of Solidarity since 1972.
This year the Week falls on May 25 till May 29.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the Non-Aligned-Movement (NAM),
Colombia's representative Alvago Forero told the Committee that
the recent Ministerial Meeting of the NAM Coordinating Bureau
reaffirmed the principle of self-determination, irrespective of
the Territories' size. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
