<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria FM Expresses Optimism on Middle East Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, MAY 22 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara on Friday expressed little optimism on reviving the
deadlocked Middle East peace process because of Israel's policy.
</P>
<P>
"There is not much optimism," Shara told reporters after his
talks with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright at the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
"I tell you frankly, although I didn't hear it directly from
the American side, it was obvious that the Israeli government
policy is the major factor in the deadlock in the peace process
which we witness now," he said.
</P>
<P>
Syria has held sporadic peace talks with Israel since 1991 but
the negotiations broke off in early 1996 without making tangible
progress on two major issues -- the fate of the Golan Heights and
future ties between Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
No talks have been held since right-wing Likud leader Benjamin
Netanyahu won an election in May 1996 and took office as the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants the talks to resume from the point where they left
off, but Netanyahu, who opposes returning the Golan Heights to
Syria, wants to start talks anew.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to resume the talks from where we stopped,"
Shara reiterated on Friday.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Lebanon, both Damascus and Beirut rejected
Israel's proposal for withdrawal from south Lebanon on the
condition that Lebanese army takes control of the area and
prevents guerrilla attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syria ad Lebanon say Israel should implement U.N. Resolution
425, passed in 1978, which calls for an unconditional pullback
of Israel's 35,000 troops. And Shara also reaffirmed the Syrian
position on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
