<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Close on N.Irish Peace Deal with High Turnout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- All the polls closed at 2200 on
Friday (2100 GMT) in Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic for
the referendum on the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The voting underwent peacefully with a heavy turnout on both
sides of the border. An estimated 80 percent of the Northern Irish
electorate had cast their ballots, according to BBC report.
</P>
<P>
In some areas of the province, queues formed outside polling
stations even before they opened. Nearly four million people --
1.2 million in the North and 2.8 million in the south -- were
eligible to cast a ballot.
</P>
<P>
The referendum, which decides the fate of Northern Ireland,
marked the first all-Ireland poll in 80 years.
</P>
<P>
Chief Electoral Officer Pat Bradley, who is running the vote in
Northern Ireland, said figures from a polling station in Belfast
indicated a final turnout in excess of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
"It's been very consistent and persistent," he said, adding
that the result would be expected by Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
If the peace agreement is endorsed by the voters on both sides
of the border, it will pave the way for a new Northern Ireland
assembly designed to secure a say for both the Protestant majority
and the 40 percent Roman Catholic minority.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace deal, Northern Ireland will remain in Britain
while building closer ties with Ireland.
</P>
<P>
There has been no reports of any incidents so far. Police
officers -- some clutching Heckler and Koch assault rifles --
patrolled in and near polling stations in case of attacks by
dissident groups opposed to the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Voting was also brisk in the Irish republic, where the
electorate was being asked to drop its historical constitutional
claim on the six northern counties, according to reports from
Dublin, the Irish capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
