<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House of Representatives Debates Campaign Finance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Friday started debating campaign finance
legislation, with one side criticizing the huge spending on
federal elections and the other countering that the bills under
consideration would violate the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The debate suspended after two hours and will be resumed when
lawmakers return after a weeklong holiday recess starting
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"This debate will clearly identify those members who support
real bipartisan reform... from those who are tied to the status
quo," said Representative Marty Meehan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
Meehan and Republican Representative Christopher Shays
co-sponsored a bipartisan bill to ban "soft money," -- unregulated
campaign donations to national and state parties from
corporations, labor unions and individuals.
</P>
<P>
The Shays-Meehan proposal is supported by many members of the
Senate, where a Republican filibuster derailed nearly identical
campaign finance legislation last Winter. President Bill Clinton
and some consumer groups also back the bill.
</P>
<P>
When the House reconvenes next month, debate is expected to
focus initially on a competing proposal drafted by a bipartisan
group of first-termers. The bill would ban "soft money" at the
federal level only, increase contribution limits and require
additional disclosures from outside groups.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the reform said that the issue is really about
free speech, and that limiting the amount of money in campaigns
would restrict that cherished constitutional right.
</P>
<P>
But Representative Asa Hutchinson, a Republican and a leading
sponsor of the freshmen bill, countered that reform opponents were
waging a "misinformation campaign" about the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
"By claiming to argue for free speech, the opponents of reform
are cynically attempting to make sure that big money not only
talks but it screams," he said.
</P>
<P>
The national political parties raised 67.4 million dollars in
"soft money" in 1997, the biggest amount of "soft money" ever
raised in an off-election year, according to a recent analysis by
Common Cause, a public interest group that supports the
Shays-Meehan bill. Republicans raised nearly 50 percent more than
Democrats during the period, 40.4 million dollars compared with 27
million dollars, according to the Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders of the House of Representatives oppose curbs
on campaign spending, but agreed to debate the issue a second time
this year under intense pressure from rank-and-file members.
</P>
<P>
"What they really are doing is trying to hide behind the First
Amendment," said Ann McBride, executive director of Common Cause.
"This is not a debate about free speech. It's a debate about very
expensive speech from very huge contributions flooding the
system."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
