<HEADLINE> World Gold Demand Falls 55 pct in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- World gold demand fell by 55 percent
in the first three months of this year as a result of Asia's
economic crisis, the first significant fall in gold consumption in
six years, according to a latest survey by the World Gold Council
(WGC).
</P>
<P>
The council's quarterly Gold Demand Trend survey showed that
gold demand in the three months to the end of March fell to 342.1
tons or 11 million troy ounces, the first big fall since the
survey began in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The council, which monitors 21 countries accounting for about
80 percent of global demand, said in its survey that the Asian
financial crisis helped slash demand for gold in developing Asian
countries by 70 percent during the first quarter of this year
compared with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It said that Indonesian gold demand crashed by 152 percent in
the first quarter against the same period last year, South Korean
demand down by 723 percent, Malaysian by 80 percent and in Japan,
demand fell by 40 percent, followed by Singapore's 28 percent
drop.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, consumers in Asian countries have dumped over 268
tons of gold coins, jewellery and other bullion on world markets
in the first quarter, nearly 10 percent of total annual world
demand, in an effort to help their countries to pay off some of
their debts.
</P>
<P>
Patriotic South Koreans alone handed over 228 tons of gold to
their government in the state-sponsored "save the nation" gold
collections movement.
</P>
<P>
Indonesians also sold a net 64 tons of gold to the world
market, some times to buy necessities after the value of their
domestic currency collapsed.
</P>
<P>
This contributed to drive down the price of the precious metal
to a 18.5-year low of 276.50 U.S. dollars an ounce on January 13
from about 417 U.S. dollars in February last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
