<HEADLINE> EU Deeply Concerned over Algeria Bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) Friday
expressed grave concern over the latest bomb blast in Algeria and
called for immediate end to the violence.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 14 people were killed and 33 wounded in a
bomb blast at a market in a suburb of Algiers early Friday and it
was the second bomb attack over the past 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office minister Derek Fatchett, whose country
is the current EU president, said in a statement issued Friday
afernoon: "Today's bombings near Algiers provide a grim reminder
of the appalling violence which the Algerian people continue to
suffer."
</P>
<P>
Fatchett stressed the 15-nation bloc remains " deeply concerned
about the latest deaths and injuries and renew its calls on the
perpetrators for an immediate end to these brutal attacks."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 65,000 people have been killed in
violence in Algeria since early 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
